<HEAD>Doctor Cleared in Dog-Pig Spat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOUNT LEBANON, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A doctor committed no crime when he brandished a pistol at a dog that went after his miniature pig in his backyard, a judge ruled. District Justice <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Ivill </PERSON> on Wednesday dismissed charges against Dr. <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Barrera </PERSON>, 36, who was charged with recklessly endangering another person, simple assault and disorderly conduct in the incident. <PERSON> Barrera </PERSON>'s neighbor, <PERSON> Melvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON>, testified he and his wife were caring for a stray dog, a young Siberian husky weighing about 40 pounds, when the dog got away from him and went after <PERSON> Barrera </PERSON>'s miniature pig next door <PERSON> Barrera </PERSON> started waving a pistol at the dog but `` did not point the gun directly at me,'' <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON> said. But, <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON> said, `` I felt like I was being intimidated.'' Testimony showed that neither animal was injured and no shots were fired in this <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> suburb. <PERSON> Ivill </PERSON> said <PERSON> Barrera </PERSON> was on his own property and was licensed to carry a gun. He ruled <PERSON> Barrera </PERSON> was a man `` preparing to defend his pet from a trespassing animal.'' <PERSON> Barrera </PERSON> said he obtained the gun for protection and the pig because `` I'm asthmatic and allergic to dogs and cats.''
