<HEAD>Space Shuttle Managers To Set Discovery Launch Date</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Late afternoon announcement expected.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Launch of the Discovery and its five-astronaut crew could be scheduled for late next week as <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> prepares for the third post-Challenger shuttle mission. <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> officials, who planned to announce a launch date today, said Wednesday the liftoff would occur no sooner than March 11 because of the need to replace a failed electrical part in one of the shuttle's three main engines The target date had been March 9, but the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> told <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> Monday that it planned to launch a high-priority military rocket on that day and could not support a shuttle flight with <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> tracking facilities. The electrical part problem apparently took care of that potential conflict. But a delay in the military flight could affect the shuttle launch on a day-by-day basis. The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> mission has priority for national security reasons. During five days in orbit, Discovery's astronauts are to deploy a large communications satellite and conduct scientific experiments.
