<FIRST>r a PM-Networks-Sweep     03-03 0600</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Networks-Sweep,0618</SECOND>
<HEAD>NBC, CBS Rebound from Strike; ABC Still Struggling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The so-called February ratings sweep indicate <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> have rebounded from last year's writers' strike, but network executives say the September-April `` season'' used to track the ratings race should be yearlong. `` I know you guys love races,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Poltrack </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> vice president for marketing, `` but any discussion of full-season results is a historical curiosity and not a marketing issue, and a disservice to us.'' <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Wurtzel </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>'s senior vice president for marketing and research, said the season race is now `` a spectator sport'' and means nothing except for bragging rights. `` In 1989, to say there is a ` season' is so antiquated,'' said <PERSON> Wurtzel </PERSON>. `` That means we would be abdicating the audience five months of the year, and that's not something we can afford to do.'' <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Entertainment </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Brandon </PERSON> <PERSON> Tartikoff </PERSON> has long held that the ratings race season should be year-round, too, but such talk did n't come up at Thursday's <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> briefing on the February sweep rating period _ one of four months a year when local TV ratings are measured to determine advertising rates. But then, <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> is winning another season hands-down. Ten years ago when the average viewer had few channels available, the networks did n't have to worry about losing their audience to competition from cable or videocassettes over the summer, but times have changed. The audience that has access to an average of 25 channels will go elsewhere if the networks fail to offer them what they want to watch. In February, the networks did. The <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> miniseries `` Lonesome Dove'' and the heated competition it encouraged boosted the networks' aggregate rating after a more than yearlong decline. The four-night `` Lonesome Dove'' boosted third-place CBS above <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> in the February sweep and makes second place for the season a tossup. <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> won the sweep with an average <ORGANIZATION> A.C. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nielsen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> rating of 16.3. <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> had a 14.7 and <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> a 12.4. The rating is a percentage of 90.4 million <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> homes with televisions. <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> had a 28 percent decline in February compared to February 1988, when it had the Winter Olympics. <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> showed increases this February over last. <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> was forced, because of the writers' strike, to run the first 18-hour stretch of its 32-hour miniseries `` War and Remembrance'' in November. Hardly a ratings blockbuster, it still did better than <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>'s regular programming. The decision to run the program then came back to haunt the network in February when `` War and Remembrance'' was to have run. `` Clearly we had a disappointing sweeps,'' said <PERSON> Wurtzel </PERSON>. `` We did not have an enormous inventory, because we had to play ` War and Remembrance' early, and we had planned to play it in February,'' he said. `` The other two networks knew that and planned accordingly.'' CBS got a big push, both in ratings and morale, from the critically acclaimed `` Lonesome Dove,'' the highest-rated network miniseries in more than four years. But the miniseries' success pleased <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>, too. `` I think ` Lonesome Dove' was beneficial to everybody,'' said <PERSON> Wurtzel </PERSON>. `` Network television needs to have exciting, well-made programming.'' <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> even used figures from the week of `` Lonesome Dove'' to contend that network `` reach'' has not declined in the past decade, even if ratings have. `` Say we -LRB- the networks -RRB- are all throwing a party,'' explained <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaffe </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s vice president for research projects. `` The same number of people come to the party, but instead of staying 2 -LCB- hours, maybe they stay two hours, then they go to someone else's party.''
</TEXT>
