<FIRST>r i PM-Gorbachev     03-03 1012</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gorbachev,1037</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Still Seeks `Better Life' After 4 Years In Power</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 It will be four years on March 11 that <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> came to power in the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION>, instituting a policy of restructuring to the Soviet system and bringing about a greater openess of that closed society. Following is the first of a series of reports by <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> correspondents in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> assaying those four years.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL PUTZEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> says he was once asked by a farmer what he was trying to accomplish with all his reforms. `` Simply, we want, in spite of everything ... for working people to lead a better life,'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said he replied. `` I thought it was enough to say.'' Perhaps it's as simple as that: the quaint wish of a Russian peasant's son who grew up in such hardship that at one point he was kept out of school for want of shoes. But he was taught to dream in the time of <PERSON> Nikita </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Khrushchev </PERSON>, another reformist Soviet leader of humble origins, and indications are <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> dreams of grander, more profound changes not just for the people but for the state. Seventy years after the Russian Revolution, the Soviet economy is in serious trouble and communism has not provided a better life for workers who yearn for bigger apartments, better working conditions, more nourishing and varied food. And an economy ruled from the center has not kept pace with the technology of the West. In what would by American measure be a full presidential term, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has made wholesale changes in the way the world perceives him and the nation he leads. He has thrown open prisons and labor camps and, in some cases, borders to free thousands of political prisoners and permit tens of thousands of people to leave the country. He has eased, although certainly not eliminated, the fear of foreigners. Under `` glasnost'' he has converted the mass media from a tightly controlled propaganda organ to a braying calliope of complaints, debates, exposes and experiments testing just how far the new openness may go _ and to what purpose. Yet for all his effort, the changes at home have been largely atmospheric. His plans for `` perestroika,'' or restructuring Soviet society, have faltered. The forces that keep this vast nation a drab, monolithic parody of the communist state envisioned by its founders resist each tangible step toward that `` better life'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> seeks for those he calls `` the simple people who are the salt of our countries.'' Store shelves are barren. Meat, butter, cheese and sugar are widely rationed. Such simple necessities as winter boots and windshield wipers are perpetually unavailable, and consumers may wait for years to buy long-outdated models of `` modern conveniences'' such as washing machines, cars or even electric irons. The air in urban areas is filthy, the water unreliable, living quarters poorly planned and filled far beyond capacity. Crash construction programs produce instant ruins: crumbling high rises barely habitable by the time they are occupied years after their first cracked concrete slabs were laid to start them on their way. One of the imponderables of this tumultuous time is how long even a remarkably dynamic and politically astute leader has to accomplish the goals he has set for himself, fighting the shortcomings of the system and inertia-bound bureaucrats. One simple measure of how long the road is and how much time progress takes: Last summer, the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> set as a national goal the installation of a telephone in just one-half of all Soviet homes by 1995. People in urban areas wait years for a phone, and many rural districts do n't have any service. Villagers five miles from <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> draw their water from community wells. It is a fundamental tenet of official <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> analysis that the `` better life'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> seeks for his countrymen is not an end in itself but the means of maintaining his nation's superpower status in a fast-changing world. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, according to that view, can no longer afford its own military might and ca n't use its power to keep pace with _ or even steal _ the technology that is quickly increasing the gulf between the industrialized West and the long-stagnant East. As <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has pressed for more discussion of problems, modernization of services, development of private initiative and greater public participation in the political process, Westerners have been tempted to think he is trying to fashion a nation resembling the world's other great superpower, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. A pragmatic leader who calls himself a realist, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> repeatedly insists he intends to work within the framework of socialism. Both he and <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Yakovlev </PERSON>, said to be his closest adviser, have written books critical of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and what they said was its intolerance for other ways of life and thought. Regardless of any personal vision, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> is pushed by economic reality to reorder Soviet priorities. `` He does n't have the resources to sustain the investments the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> is making in foreign policy and defense,'' said one Western analyst who discussed the issue on condition he not be identified. <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> estimates the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> devotes 15 percent to 25 percent of its gross national product to the military. `` Even the lower end of that range would be enormous by world standards,'' the analyst said. `` The upper end is truly staggering. But that's not all, because that same 15 to 25 percent monopolizes the country's scientific and technological resources and people.'' To begin reducing those figures, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> already has negotiated the first treaty reducing <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> nuclear arsenals and has announced substantial unilateral reductions in Soviet grounds forces at home and abroad, including this month's completion of the withdrawal from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. `` Part of the reordering of priorities is to work on what <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> calls the ` enemy image,''' the analyst said. `` He has to persuade other leaders he's serious and lower the perception of risk in the rest of the world.''
</TEXT>
