<HEAD>Beirut Vintner Dodges Bombs To Make Great Wine</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK SCHREIBMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Winemaker <PERSON> Serge </PERSON> <PERSON> Hochar </PERSON>, like some of his competitors, likes to sell no wine before its time. But in war-torn <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, it's not always up to him to decide. `` You never know if you'll be hit,'' <PERSON> Hochar </PERSON> said Wednesday, adding that he's missed some vintages when fighting broke out near his Chateau Musar, the best-known of <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s five wineries. `` I must say, I have been very lucky,'' said the vintner, whose products are internationally rated among the top wines of the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>. `` My home, 200 yards from the fire line between east and west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, has been bombed only three times in the last 14 years, and I managed to escape.'' The Beirut-born winemaker, who is in his 50s, styles his wine for cosmopolitan tastes. He was in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> on Wednesday on a seven-city <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> tour to market his wines, which ranged from 1959 to 1980. Despite his unpredictable environment, <PERSON> Hochar </PERSON> says he will not release a vintage if he does n't like it, and he insists on holding his wines in cellars for at least eight years. `` I am not a political man. I am a wine man, and a wine man is a human person because I work with life. I keep my vines and my wines alive,'' he said. Hochar makes 15,000 to 20,000 cases of wine a year at the 30-year-old winery founded by his father, <PERSON> Gaston </PERSON>. The star is his <ORGANIZATION> Bordeaux </ORGANIZATION> red, a blend of cabernet sauvignon, cinsault and syrah. It can take weeks for <LOCATION> Hochar </LOCATION> to get grapes from the <LOCATION> Bekaa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>, 40 miles south of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, to his winery in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s embattled capital city. `` We have to cross five or six checkpoints, many borders ... sometimes we have to go south from the vineyard and sail back by boat.'' And everywhere, he said, he must pay duty, at each border and to whomever has the power _ or a gun. `` You get used to it after a while,'' he said. `` You do n't realize you are in a war situation You live with it. ... In <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, you can always manage to find a few friends to make things easier.''
