<FIRST>r a AM-ReactorBarge     03-03 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Reactor Barge,0366</SECOND>
<HEAD>Barge Moving Decommissioned Reactor On 8,100-Mile Water Trip</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> barge carrying a 1,000-ton nuclear reactor from the nation's first decommissioned commercial nuclear power plant passed this city Thursday on its two-month, 8,100-mile trip to burial at <LOCATION> Hanford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION> `` There's a bit of history here,'' said <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> McKerman </PERSON>, a consultant to the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> on the project. `` I like to think of it as the end of the beginning of nuclear power.'' <PERSON> McKernan </PERSON> said the nuclear plant at <LOCATION> Shippingport </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, was the first commercial nuclear plant to be commissioned in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the first to be decommissioned. It is the first in the world to be dismantled. <ORGANIZATION> Duquesne </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Light </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> began operating the plant in 1957 and closed it down in 1982. <ORGANIZATION> Duquesne </ORGANIZATION> operates two other nuclear power plants at <LOCATION> Shippingport </LOCATION>, about 35 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> along the <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>. Earlier this month, the reactor was mounted on the barge <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Bunyan </PERSON>. The barge, pushed by the motor vessel <PERSON> Pere </PERSON> <PERSON> Marquette </PERSON>, left <LOCATION> Shippingport </LOCATION> on Tuesday for <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> DOE </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Bauman </PERSON> said. `` The DOE has spent a lot of money on this thing to make sure it is safe,'' said <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Zupon </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineers </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>. `` You could sit on top of this thing and ride it down the river with no threat of radiation.'' `` We are being updated on the tow's progress twice a day,'' <PERSON> McKerman </PERSON> said. `` So far, there have been no problems. It is moving along just as it was planned.'' The reactor, which is 35 feet long and 25 feet high and encased in concrete, is being shipped to an Energy Department disposal site for burial, <PERSON> Bauman </PERSON> said. The vessel will take the <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> to the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, to the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, to the <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canal </LOCATION>, and the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> north to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state. The journey is expected to take about 60 days, officials said. The reactor parts were packed in concrete before being loaded onto the <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Bunyan </PERSON> last month, but the trip was delayed because of bad weather, <PERSON> Bauman </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
