<FIRST>r w PM-TheMonthly'sFolly Bjt   03-03 0718</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-The Monthly's Folly, Bjt,730</SECOND>
<HEAD>Magazine Boss Asks Former Employees to Set Him Straight</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE FEINSILBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Randolph </PERSON> <PERSON> Hearst </PERSON> could n't have put it clearer. `` Why,'' asked editor <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Peters </PERSON>, summing up the philosophy that has guided his magazine for 20 years, `` should I publish something I do n't agree with?'' Nonetheless, to celebrate a survival that was never a sure thing, the March issue of <PERSON> Peters </PERSON>' skinny magazine, the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> Monthly, violates his own premise. `` What's Wrong With This Magazine?'' asks the cover. Inside, 11 former editors are allowed to take issue with the boss, one of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s enduring curmudgeons. The result: the reader gets to watch liberalism argue with itself. None of March's contributors quarrels with the Monthly's fundamental liberal philosophy _ one it is no more likely to abandon than Popular Mechanics would question the utility of the basement workbench But, like <ORGANIZATION> Popular </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mechanics </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Peters </PERSON>' magazine has been concerned with the way things actually work and why they do n't if they do n't. His view is that they often do n't; his goal is `` to expose and correct the follies of liberalism.'' He calls it neoliberalism. `` We were not trying to move the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> to the right,'' recalls former Monthly writer <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Lemann </PERSON>. `` We were trying to make liberalism even better and stronger than it already was.'' Like scores of other onetime Monthly writers, <PERSON> Lemann </PERSON> moved on to better pay, in his case at the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Peters </PERSON> paid his editors $ 10,000 a year _ himself $ 24,000 _ but gave them the chance to write and be read in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. The magazine has 33,000 subscribers and, after a long struggle, is in the black. <PERSON> Peters </PERSON>, a former <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> legislator and <ORGANIZATION> Peace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> executive, founded it with some help from investors including Sen. <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Rockefeller </PERSON>, D-W. <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, a fellow former Peace <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Levine </PERSON>, now with <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; World Report, takes the Monthly to task for not coming to grips with the full consequences of its advocacy of a less greedy way of life. `` If we're to be less materialistic ... it means that we'll buy fewer products and there will be less revenue for business. The hard question that neoliberals and others have n't asked is: Can we have more time for families and volunteerism, less materialism, and still have high economic growth? I do n't think so.'' <PERSON> Gregg </PERSON> <PERSON> Easterbrook </PERSON>, now a contributing editor of <ORGANIZATION> Newsweek </ORGANIZATION>, accuses the Monthly of harboring an unwholesome suspicion of profits. `` Occasionally companies make big profits via fraud, monopoly or other chicanery,'' he writes. `` Usually they make big profits because they deserve to _ the market is pretty effective in distributing that reward.'' Anyway, asks <PERSON> Easterbrook </PERSON>, what's so bad about the `` service-yuppie-paper economy'' that <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> is becoming? `` The Monthly often laments that the backbreaking, dangerous, soul-draining jobs in heavy industrial production are being replaced by highly paid white-collar desk jobs. Sounds pretty good to me.'' <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Kinsley </PERSON>, now editor of The <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION>, attacks <PERSON> Peters </PERSON>' perennial crusade for a peacetime draft `` Telling people they must give up two years of their lives is a major infringement on freedom,'' <PERSON> Kinsley </PERSON> argues. Moreover, if rich people were drafted into the Army they would push out poor people who are there because they want to be, he says. `` It's no favor to would-be volunteers to shut off this option in order to put others unwillingly in their place.'' <PERSON> Peters </PERSON> gives himself the last word, accepting many of the criticisms but taking issue with others. To <PERSON> Easterbrook </PERSON>, he says that what's wrong with maximizing profits `` is that it encourages corporations to take chances with worker safety, to pollute the air, to attempt to gain monopoly control of markets.'' To <PERSON> Levine </PERSON>'s growth arguments, he says, `` Without economic growth, we wo n't have the tax revenues necessary to clear up the environmental mess that already exists.'' And to <PERSON> Kinsley </PERSON> he says a draft would give <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> at least one social institution where rich and poor could come to know and understand one another. `` Upper-class participation in the military would give people with clout a compelling interest in avoiding war and, in case war turns out to be unavoidable, in being equipped with weapons that work,'' <PERSON> Peters </PERSON> writes. `` Thus a draft of the wealthy would both aid military reformers and enhance the prospect for peace.''
</TEXT>
