<HEAD>Labor and Business Await Bush Decision on Airline Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s decision on whether to intervene in the threatened <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> strike will show whether he wants to improve relations with organized labor, a union president says. <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> <PERSON> Sombrotto </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Letter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carriers </ORGANIZATION>, said that if <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> appoints an emergency investigative board and delays the strike by 60 days, `` that would show a recognition of American labor as an institution.'' But if <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> refuses to invoke the law, <PERSON> Sombrotto </PERSON> said, `` that would just be consistent with the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration's laissez-faire attitude. Former President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> responded to his first labor-management crisis in August 1981 by firing some 11,400 striking air traffic controllers, and <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s relations with organized labor suffered throughout two terms. Now, the specter of a strike at 12:01 a.m. EST Saturday has forced <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to decide whether he wants to invoke provisions of the Railway Labor Act to impose a 60-day cooling off period. <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Kahn </PERSON>, who headed the now-defunct <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> and was chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wage </ORGANIZATION> and Price Stability during the <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> administration, said it would be a mistake to intervene. But <PERSON> Audrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Freeman </PERSON>, an analyst with the private <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, said she doubted that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s decision either way would make a major statement about his intentions toward labor. `` I do n't think the controllers strike changed the course of history of labor-management relations,'' she said, `` and I do n't think that whatever Mr. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will do will change the course of labor relations. At midnight, the end of a 30-day cooling-off period set by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mediation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> can impose work conditions and the union can strike. The board recommended that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> name the emergency panel. <PERSON> Kahn </PERSON>, who was instrumental in the late 1970s move to ease government regulation of the airline industry and increase competition, said, `` I think that if the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration succumbs, and appoints this board ... it would be tipping the scales in favor of labor. It would be such a labor-dictated intervention it could be seen as killing Eastern.'' <PERSON> Kahn </PERSON>, in a telephone interview from the campus of <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, said `` the more they -LRB- the unions -RRB- can delay either a strike or the probability of a settlement, the more they can increase the chances of Eastern going under.'' <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Bernardo </PERSON>, special counsel to the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION>, said the union movement is `` going to unduly pressure the new administration ... by raising the stakes'' in situations such as the Eastern dispute. `` It's a fairly dangerous gambit, forcing this into an early bellwether of where the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration is going to go'' in the area of labor-relations, he said. `` Government intervention was not a hallmark of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration. `` If he -LRB- <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> -RRB- makes the decision to intervene, it will be a reluctant one,'' de <PERSON> Bernardo </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Sombrotto </PERSON> acknowledged that `` it's a little unusual'' for organized labor to urge government intervention to stop a strike _ which is the ultimate weapon of unionized workers. But he said that `` it is a little different period.'' He said a strike would be detrimental to `` the flying public'' and to the economy, as well as to the <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> employees. In contrast to earlier years, when the organized labor movement was much stronger, the <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION> has urged <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to use this law to delay a strike. In days past, government intervention to stop a strike would have infuriated labor leaders. At the same time, <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>, the chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which owns <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>, has warned that putting off planned cuts in costs could send the carrier to `` the corporate graveyard.''
