<FIRST>r w PM-Congress-Poet     03-03 0605</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Congress-Poet,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poet Laureate Nemerov Honors Congress with His Verse</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Poet Laureate <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Nemerov </PERSON> says writing a poem about <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> was `` a real hard test,'' but he thinks the 28 lines he penned to help the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> observe their 200th anniversary served the purpose. <PERSON> Nemerov </PERSON> read his poem at a joint meeting of the two Houses Thursday _ held early because the bicentennial of March 4, 1789, when the first <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> met in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, will fall on a Saturday when <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is not in session. `` I think the historian of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> was the one who transmitted the invitation, and I said, ` Well, what the hell, have a go, <PERSON> Howard </PERSON>,''' said the poet. `` I'm not a romantic poet, but I do n't mind trying to do a decent job of whatever comes up, and if I ca n't do it, I wo n't,'' he said. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> historian, <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Smock </PERSON>, said he asked <PERSON> Nemerov </PERSON> about three weeks ago if he would write the poem. `` I simply called him up and told him we would like to have this happen, and he was delighted,'' he said. `` You could see that already the wheels were turning and he was thinking about <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and saw it, I think, as a challenge.'' <PERSON> Nemerov </PERSON> said it was n't any cinch turning out a poem about <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in three weeks. `` It cost a lot of blood and sweat to do it,'' he said. `` If there were time, I would have told the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, ` I was brought up to believe that no subject was intrinsically unpoetical, but you ladies and gents gave me a real hard test.' However, I think I done all right.'' <PERSON> Smock </PERSON> said the lawmakers `` thought it was just the right touch.'' <PERSON> Nemerov </PERSON>'s poem, entitled `` To the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> Entering its Third Century,'' ends with the lines: `` So it's a republic, as <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> said, `` If you can keep it; and we did `` This far, and hope to keep our quarrel `` Funny and just, though with this moral: `` Praise without end for the go-ahead zeal `` Of whoever it was invented the wheel; `` But never a word for the poor soul's sake `` That thought ahead, and invented the brake.'' <PERSON> Nemerov </PERSON> is the third person to serve as poet laureate, following <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Penn </PERSON> <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> and <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilbur </PERSON>, under a 1986 law adding that title to the 50-year-old position of consultant in poetry to the Library of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. The law includes a clause that provides, `` Each department and office of the federal government is encouraged to make use of the services of the poet laureate for ceremonial and other occasions of celebration.'' Poets took exception when the law was written. `` I can see all sorts of terrible things possibly happening,'' <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> Kunitz </PERSON>, the 1979 winner of the Pulitzer Prize for poetry, said at a conference at <ORGANIZATION> George </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. `` Relations between politics and poetry have been almost always destructive to poetry,'' added <PERSON> Josephine </PERSON> <PERSON> Jacobsen </PERSON>, like <PERSON> Kunitz </PERSON> a former Library of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> poetry consultant. But <PERSON> Nemerov </PERSON> says he never heard of such a provision. <PERSON> Smock </PERSON> said he and other Bicentennial planners knew what the law said, but that was n't why they decided to ask <PERSON> Nemerov </PERSON> if he would write a poem. `` It was more a feeling that this occasion called for a poetic expression,'' said <PERSON> Smock </PERSON>. `` I do n't know what's happened to poetry,'' <PERSON> Smock </PERSON> said. `` It seems to have retreated to our universities, and its not something that's done publicly like it used to be. We thought it would be delightful to afford the poet laureate an opportunity if he was willing.''
