<HEAD>Fed Chief Says Money Moves Have Kept Inflation at Bay</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> insists that the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>'s anti-inflation moves have been proper despite criticism that its tight-money policy could topple the country into a recession,. <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday that he did not believe forcing the country into a recession was a proper way to fight inflation and he said that was not the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>'s intention. But he said if the central bank had not been pursuing a policy of gradually pushing up interest rates since March of last year, inflationary pressures would be much more severe at the current time. If inflation gets out of control, the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> is forced to squeeze credit much tighter, driving interest rates even higher and making any economic downturn much more severe. That is what occurred in 1981-82, when the country suffered through the most drastic recession since the Great Depression, as then-Fed Chairman <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Volcker </PERSON> drove interest rates higher and higher to combat the worst bout of inflation since the Civil War. <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> indicated that the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>'s current course was aimed at making sure that the next recession will not have to be as severe. `` I do believe that the business cycle has not been repealed,'' <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> said. `` We will at some point get a recession, but I hope that we have correct policies in place so the recession will be mild.'' <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> <PERSON> Panetta </PERSON>, D-Calif., noted that there was a difference of opinion on the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>'s credit-tightening moves, which included a decision last Friday to boost to 7 percent the discount rate, the interest the central bank charges to make loans to financial institutions `` Opinion seems divided whether this move was ` too little, too late' or ` too much, too soon,' `` <PERSON> Panetta </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Panetta </PERSON> said that regardless of whether the higher interest rates end up pushing the country into a recession, the credit tightening will have many adverse consequences, including a bigger budget deficit, more troubles for the savings and loan industry, higher debt payments by Third World countries and higher costs to consumers who borrow to purchase homes and autos. But <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> said the central bank remained convinced that the dangers of doing nothing outweighed risks to specific sectors of the economy from higher interest rates. On another matter, <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> said he still supported increasing the federal gasoline tax but only as a conservation measure, not as a way of boosting federal revenues. <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> also said that boosting taxes on alcoholic beverages and cigarettes would not harm the economy, but he said simply increasing federal tax revenues was not the answer the government's imbalance between spending and revenues Echoing a position taken by President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and former President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> said that higher federal revenues were much more likely to end up funding new programs rather than being used to reduce the budget deficit. `` There is a tendency in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, when revenues are available, to increase government programs,'' <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> said he would prefer across-the-board spending cuts to tax increases if <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the administration fail to agree on a plan to reduce the 1990 budget deficit to $ 100 billion. <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> repeated warnings that he has made in earlier congressional appearances that it is crucial that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the new administration reach agreement on a credible, multi-year plan to reduce the budget deficit. He said there was `` no question'' that such a deficit-reduction program would encourage financial investors and allow long-term interest rates to fall substantially.
</TEXT>
