<HEAD>Holes In Cows For Feed Test Prompts Protests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Swedish research project in which two cows had holes sliced in their stomachs to test different types of food has prompted protests by animal rights activists. Swedish papers Thursday published pictures of one of the cows, <PERSON> Norma </PERSON>, with a hole into her flank that was large enough for a man to put in his arm and insert a plastic feed bag into her stomach. The study at <ORGANIZATION> Skara </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Veterinary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> was to determine whether cows could convert as much nourishment from domestic feed as from imported grains. The feed bags, similar to tea bags, are inserted and withdrawn several times a day. In between, the holes are closed with plastic plugs. The study involves 40 cows, half fed Swedish-grown foodstuffs and the rest on imported grains. The Animal Protection Board in <LOCATION> Goteborg </LOCATION> expressed dismay at the project, and the research farm reportedly was flooded with letters from offended citizens. `` I can understand if many people react negatively to this. But I can guarantee that the cows are not adversely affected by the hole,'' <PERSON> Bo </PERSON> <PERSON> Pehrsson </PERSON>, the veterinarian leading the project, was quoted as saying. He said farmers could save up to $ 158 per cow annually if domestic feed replaces imported grains.
