<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Corn and sorghum growers who participated in last year's feed grain program will get about $ 125 million from the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> this month. <PERSON> Milton </PERSON> <PERSON> Hertz </PERSON>, executive vice president of the department's <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, said Thursday the payments will be in the form of generic certificates, which are redeemable in surplus commodities held by the CCC About $ 85 million will be paid to eligible corn farmers and $ 40 million to sorghum producers. Most corn farmers, upon request, were paid about $ 2.6 billion at the time they signed up in the 1988 program, and sorghum farmers collected about $ 288 million in advance payments, <ORGANIZATION> Hertz </ORGANIZATION> said.
