<HEAD>Report Criticizes EPA Handling of Grants for Community Groups</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> is making it difficult for citizen groups near Superfund hazardous waste sites to participate in a grant program, a congressional report says. The program, which provides up to $ 50,000 in grants for community groups to hire technical experts, is n't working, Rep. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Florio </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.J. </LOCATION>, said Thursday after releasing the report with Rep. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Markey </PERSON>, D-Mass. While some community groups described <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> staff as helpful to applicants, `` many more commented that they were actively discouraged from applying or expressed the belief that the agency could not be interested ... based on the cumbersome process it had established,'' the report said. The report, based on a survey of 72 people and community groups, concluded the Technical Assistance Grant program was plagued by a long application process, difficult-to-understand forms and <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> staff resistance. <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Kovalick </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, deputy director of <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Emergency </ORGANIZATION> and Remedial Response, said, `` Trying to empower citizen groups is a very difficult task when trying to balance fiscal responsibility and being as helpful as we can to community groups.'' He said <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> is trying to improve the program, and emphasized it was not agency policy to discourage participation. Grants are available at each of the 1,175 Superfund hazardous waste sites, so that community groups can get the technical information needed for a voice in cleanup operations. <PERSON> Kovalick </PERSON> said 13 grants have been awarded so far, and the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> is considering an additional 79 letters expressing interest. The survey found that under the program, created in 1986: _ More than 90 percent of the community groups encountered `` major problems'' with the application process, with 9 out of 10 applicants reporting difficulty in completing paperwork One out of four applicants spent more than six weeks filling out the applications. _ <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> required that communities pay 35 percent of the technical assistance costs, although <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> recommended only a 20 percent matching requirement _ The agency agreed to waive the cost-sharing requirement only in exceptional circumstances, while <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> wanted waivers whenever needed to foster public participation The report blamed the cumbersome application process for `` discouraging affected groups from participating'' in the program, and added that the 35 percent community share makes the program `` insurmountable'' for many community organizations. <PERSON> Kovalick </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> was given discretion to choose the matching contribution for communities, and felt that by setting the figure at 35 percent, there would be more federal money to spread around.
