us school founded in 1636 to educate young men. The 10-member panel that wrote the report included three women, two blacks, a Hispanic and an <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION>. While noting that women face difficulty finding faculty openings and advancing at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION>, the panel said blacks, Hispanics and Native Americans need the most help. The pool of candidates in those groups is small and in some instances shrinking, they noted. The report advocates affirmative action, not with quotas or by stretching standards, but by looking beyond traditional routes and groups to find potential faculty. Currently, <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> has numerical targets for women and minority faculty and issues a yearly progress report, but it is not required to meet those targets. The report was considered Wednesday by the arts and sciences <ORGANIZATION> Faculty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> and is expected to go to <LOCATION> Spence </LOCATION> and the full faculty for approval later this spring. Real change will rely on new attitudes rather than administrative orders, said <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolcowitz </PERSON>, assistant dean for undergraduate education and spokesman for the faculty committee. `` If <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> as the premier institution that trains the best and the brightest is a place that is absent of the best black men and women, it sends a message that we are not very good. And many of us are,'' said <PERSON> Dean </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Watson </PERSON>, co-chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Black </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Faculty </ORGANIZATION> and Administrators. In 1980, a report prepared at the request of the school's <ORGANIZATION> Black </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Students </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> concluded that <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION>'s recruitment efforts had been passive. According to the new report, in 1978-79 just 12 women were full professors, or 3.4 percent of the total. Today they number 30 or 7.8 percent. There were 44 women on the faculty headed for tenure in 1978-79 or 19.8 percent compared with 64 and 27.7 percent now. In 1978-79 the numbers of minority full professors totaled 21, or 5.9 percent, with tenure-track teachers numbering 17, or 7.7 percent. This year there are 27 full professors, or 7 percent, and 28 minorities on the way up, or 12.1 percent. To improve hiring, the new report proposes naming a special associate dean for affirmative action in Arts and Sciences; that each faculty department designate a faculty member for that effort; and that a standing faculty committee on affirmative action be established.
