<HEAD>Warning: Rio Beaches Could Be Hazardous To Your Health</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TODD LEWAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Think twice before setting foot on the beaches of <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> de </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Janeiro </LOCATION>. Thousands of hungry little parasites are waiting hidden in the sand. A city study of <PERSON> Rio </PERSON>'s beaches that was released earlier this week says those chic beaches pictured on postcards and in international travel magazines are hardly pristine. In fact, the report warns, they're downright contaminated. `` The sand is the dirtiest it's ever been on record,'' said <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Mora </PERSON>, spokesman for <PERSON> Rio </PERSON>'s sanitation department, which conducted the study. The study, conducted last month and released Tuesday, found the sand of the toniest of <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION>'s beaches _ <LOCATION> Copacabana </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Leme </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Ipanema </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Leblon </LOCATION> _ is packed with nine types of parasites carried in animal and human feces. Among them is the potentially fatal esquistossomose parasite, which afflicts 8 million Brazilians. `` We do n't want to create a panic,'' Mayor <PERSON> Marcello </PERSON> <PERSON> Alencar </PERSON> said when he announced the study's findings. `` But the public ought to know what is happening in its city.'' <PERSON> Rio </PERSON>'s beaches, polluted in the past by chemical waste from factories and by occasional breaks in sewage lines along the beachfront, have new enemies now. They are stray animals and homeless beggars who bed down on the beaches, as well as hordes of street vendors in make-shift shacks along the shore. A week ago, in an effort to clean up the beaches, police officials raided <LOCATION> Copacabana </LOCATION> and hauled off hundreds of dollars worth of merchandise from the illegal stands parked on the beach and along the boardwalk. But the peddlers and the animals returned the next day _ with a vengeance. And the beaches took another drubbing. `` You would n't catch me taking my kids to these beaches,'' said <PERSON> Mora </PERSON>. `` The city has forgotten that it has to protect to beaches, not just rave about how pretty they are.'' He said that compared with a year ago, when the beaches were last tested for pollution, the beaches `` had gotten a lot worse.'' Despite the findings, some health experts were skeptical of the potential health threat to sunseekers. `` The sun kills the parasites on the surface,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Albeto </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Freitas </PERSON>, a disease control expert for the city. `` The danger lies in the deeper sand.'' Still, the possibility of catching a disease from the sand is greater than in past years. `` People just ought to be careful they do n't dig their feet too far under the sand,'' <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Freitas </PERSON> said. `` Otherwise, they might go home with more than a nice tan.''
