<HEAD>Battle of Bunker Hill Cannon Found</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 One of the four cannons that were all the 13 colonies had when the Revolutionary War started has been found in the basement of a police station, ending a search that began nearly 20 years ago. `` It is a priceless piece of history which could be called a national treasure,'' Capt. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Swanson </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Metrolopitan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> historian, said after cannon was found Thursday. The 3 -LCB- - foot-long, 500-pound brass cannon, believed to have been forged in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> around 1760, was found behind dozens of bicycles in a storage room that was being cleaned at the <ORGANIZATION> Metropolitan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION>'s Lower Basin <PERSON> Swanson </PERSON> said it was used in the Battle of <LOCATION> Bunker </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> on June 17, 1775. Two of the four cannons the colonies had at the start of the Revolutionary War were captured by the British. But the rediscovered cannon, now called the <PERSON> Hancock </PERSON>, and the other, now called the <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>, were hidden in a swamp in <LOCATION> Dedham </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Swanson </PERSON> said. The <PERSON> Hancock </PERSON> and the <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> were placed at the Bunker Hill Monument during the 19th century. The <ORGANIZATION> Metropolitan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> was in charge of the monument from 1919 until the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> took it over in 1975. `` When we took the site over in ` 75, there was one cannon tube -LRB- the <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> -RRB- left at the top,'' said <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Steele </PERSON>, curator of the monument. `` They were a pair. We contacted the <ORGANIZATION> MDC </ORGANIZATION> about the missing one, but no one was able to put their fingers on it. I had pretty much given up hope. This is great news.'' <PERSON> Swanson </PERSON> said he knew the cannon had been brought to the police station but no one could tell him where it was, and he had been keeping an eye out for it for 18 years. He and <PERSON> Steele </PERSON> thought it had been taken from the monument in 1970 or 1972. `` What apparently happened is that a bracket holding the cannon broke,'' <PERSON> Swanson </PERSON> said. `` It was brought to the station for safekeeping.'' <PERSON> Swanson </PERSON> said he hopes the cannon will be refurbished and placed in new brackets at the monument by June 17, Bunker Hill Day.
