<HEAD>`Lend Me A Tenor,' A New Farce, Opens On Broadway</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS three grafs of other reviews; no PMs planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Farce is built on desperation, and things do n't get more desperate than the doings at the <ORGANIZATION> Cleveland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Grand </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Opera </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION>, circa 1934 Its gala benefit performance of `` Otello'' is threatened by the apparent demise of famed Italian tenor _ and unrepentant ladies' man _ <PERSON> Tito </PERSON> <PERSON> Merelli </PERSON>. The company, along with 50 pounds of shrimp mayonnaise, may expire unless someone can be found quickly to replace the man known to his adoring fans as `` Il Stupendo.'' That is the basic setup for `` Lend Me a Tenor,'' a new farce by <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Ludwig </PERSON> that barreled into Broadway's Royale Theater on Thursday night. Although the play is slight, the evening is still delirium triumphant, primarily because of the crackerjack direction of <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Zaks </PERSON> and a superb cast led by <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Garber </PERSON> and <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Bosco </PERSON>. You'll know `` Lend Me a Tenor'' is a farce the minute the curtain rises on six smashing art deco doors scattered throughout designer <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Walton </PERSON>'s all-white hotel suite. They are waiting to be slammed. And <PERSON> Zaks </PERSON> sees that they are _ in high, often hilarious, style. Tito, of course, is not dead. He's sleeping off a combination of red wine and phenobarbital. But neither the opera company manager -LRB- <PERSON> Bosco </PERSON> -RRB- nor his milquetoast assistant <PERSON> Max </PERSON> -LRB- <PERSON> Garber </PERSON> -RRB- knows that. <PERSON> Max </PERSON>, a frustrated opera performer, rises to <PERSON> Tito </PERSON>'s high C. Slapping on blackface, a shaggy wig and the singer's purple tights, he goes on for the star, and no one knows the difference. When <PERSON> Tito </PERSON> wakes up, he dons an identical costume _ did n't you know he would carry a spare _ and suddenly there are two tenors and glorious confusion. Much of the fun is physical rather than verbal _ <PERSON> Garber </PERSON> mixing a drink with his finger, <PERSON> Bosco </PERSON> attacking a bowl of wax fruit or <PERSON> Garber </PERSON> desperately trying to wake up the horizontal tenor. <PERSON> Zaks </PERSON>' inventiveness is astonishing He has to work hard with <PERSON> Ludwig </PERSON>'s script Some of the jokes are obvious, unsurprising laughs, but <PERSON> Zaks </PERSON> does his best to divert attention from these dips in dialogue. Still, there are some very funny situations, particularly in the second act. The opera disguise allows <PERSON> Max </PERSON> to change his personality. He becomes forceful and is able to conquer the opera manager's daughter She's looking for a fling but only wants to be flung by <PERSON> Tito </PERSON>. <PERSON> Garber </PERSON> is all bumbling sweetness, a <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitty </PERSON> who discovers his voice and confidence at the same time. If <PERSON> Garber </PERSON> is all mumbles, <PERSON> Bosco </PERSON> is all roar. The actor raises apoplexy to high art, particularly in one scene when he throws himself in a rage at Tito's inert body. Seldom has such fury been so funny. <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Holgate </PERSON> ca n't quite hold onto his Italian accent, but everything else is just about right in his performance as the over-inflated Tito. He's even a fine singer. And he's perfectly matched with <PERSON> Tovah </PERSON> <PERSON> Feldshuh </PERSON> as his jealous wife who one minute is a purring pussycat, the next a snarling panther. <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith-Cameron </PERSON> is fetching as the ingenue, a stereotypical role that usually is more simpering than sexy. <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Connell </PERSON> charges merrily through the play as the chairman of the opera guild and there is other good support by <PERSON> Caroline </PERSON> <PERSON> Lagerfelt </PERSON> as an amorous soprano and <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Brooks </PERSON> as an operatic bellhop. The glamorous costumes by <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Ivey </PERSON> <PERSON> Long </PERSON> epitomize the 1930s. Some of them are even funny, particularly an evening gown for Miss <PERSON> Connell </PERSON> that makes her, in the words of another character, `` look like the Chrysler Building.'' `` Lend Me a Tenor'' is n't Feydeau _ not much is these days, particularly on <LOCATION> Broadway </LOCATION>. But it is great fun, particularly because of <PERSON> Zaks </PERSON> orchestrating all those slamming doors. In other reviews: `` Sheer craziness'' is how <PERSON> Clive </PERSON> <PERSON> Barnes </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> described the play. `` If you are feeling under the weather _ or even over the weather, for that matter _ and you believe laughter is the best medicine, let me prescribe for you this lovely dose of pure, operatic idiocy.'' <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Kissel </PERSON> in the <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> called the play enjoyable `` under <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Zaks </PERSON> brilliant direction,'' although he noted that `` the plot would not withstand intense scrutiny.'' But in The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Rich </PERSON> said the play was `` all things farcical except hilarious ... The lines are almost never witty, settling instead for double entendres ... -LRB- and -RRB- worse, too many of the farcical situations seem like pale echoes of those in similar works from the play's period.''
