<HEAD>First AIDS Cases Reported In Iran</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> recorded its first five cases of AIDS last year, the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> said today in its latest health update. The Islamic republic's report was among 2,008 new cases reported to WHO last month, bringing the total to 141,894 AIDS cases in 145 countries. Thirty-two countries said they had no cases, according to <ORGANIZATION> WHO </ORGANIZATION>'s monthly epidemiological report for February. While not previously mentioning AIDS cases, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> has reported that nearly 450 hemophiliacs, or 14 percent of the country's known hemophiliac total, carry the AIDS virus. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, which has 60 percent of all AIDS victims, accounts for most of the new cases reported to <ORGANIZATION> WHO </ORGANIZATION> in February _ 1,654. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> total rose to 86,157 victims as of Feb. 16, <ORGANIZATION> WHO </ORGANIZATION> said. <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, which has the third-highest total in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> after <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, reported 106 cases for a new total of 2,885. The <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> reported 43 new cases, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> 67, and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> 45. For <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, the new WHO bulletin listed five cases as of Dec. 31. Last month's bulletin showed no cases in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> on Dec. 31, 1987.
