<FIRST>r a PM-AbortionProtesters     03-03 0653</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion Protesters,0673</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appellate Court Upholds Protesters' RICO Violation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES WEBB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal appeals court upheld a decision that 26 anti-abortion activists had violated racketeering laws with their protests, a ruling one lawyer said `` strikes a blow at the very heart'' of the anti-abortion movement. Abortion foes and their lawyers attacked the decision, calling it a serious setback for people who practice civil disobedience. A three-judge panel of the 3rd <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday upheld a lower court decision that the protesters violated racketeering laws by conspiring to prevent abortions at <ORGANIZATION> Northeast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Women </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> clinic. The court also awarded about $ 110,000 in damages and attorneys' fees to the center. The center's lawsuit was the first test of the federal Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations Act in a civil case against abortion demonstrators, said <PERSON> Edmond </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Tiryak </PERSON>, the lawyer who brought the action for the clinic. `` From our point of view, this is an important example that will be used nationally,'' he said. The lawsuit has been used as a model by other clinics in as many as 11 other cases still at the trial level, he said. The center had charged that the protesters used force, threats and trespassing to intimidate center employees and women seeking abortions. `` What's been going on at the center has been intimidation and fear,'' said <PERSON> Tiryak </PERSON>. `` This opinion, I think, strikes a blow at the very heart of that activity by the pro-life movement.'' An anti-abortion leader named in the suit lambasted the decision but predicted it would n't stop future demonstrations. `` The American judicial system has taken a vengeance against anyone who tries to stand up for children in the womb,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> McMonagle </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> Pro-Life </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coalition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southeast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pennsylvania </ORGANIZATION>. Nevertheless, he said that since the lawsuit was filed in 1987, `` the rescue movement has taken off the ground, and <ORGANIZATION> RICO </ORGANIZATION> suits ca n't stop it now. The RICO Act has most often been used against organized crime figures, but <PERSON> Tiryak </PERSON> said it was applicable in the case because protesters used extortion _ in the form of threats and force _ to deny the center its right to operate and to deny women their right to use the center. The appelate panel unanimously upheld a June 1987 finding by a federal district jury that the protesters had engaged in a pattern of criminal activity from 1984 to 1986 designed to prevent the center from providing abortions. The appeals court said videotapes made by the center `` revealed demonstrators pushing, shoving and tugging on patients as they attempted to approach the center, knocking over and crossing police barricades and blocking the ingress of cars.'' The court rejected the protesters' argument that their actions were justified because of the issue, saying they could have used numerous legal alternatives to persuade women not to have abortions `` short of harassment.'' Tiryak contended the center lost its lease and was forced to move because of the protests. <PERSON> McMonagle </PERSON> claimed no protester was ever charged with assault, even though police were present at the demonstrations. `` Pushing does n't make a racketeer, does n't make extortionist,'' he said. <PERSON> McMonagle </PERSON> said the protesters will request that the full appeals court review the decision by the three-judge panel. The appeals court ordered the district court to further consider injunctions the center is seeking to limit the number of demonstrators outside the center and prohibit them from using bullhorns. Meanwhile, a federal judge in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> issued a temporary restraining order barring the anti-abortion group <ORGANIZATION> Operation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rescue </ORGANIZATION> from blockading women's health clinics in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> during its planned Easter week protests. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatter </PERSON>'s order, which was sought by the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, instructs protesters to stay at least 15 feet away from clinics. Operation Rescue leaders said they hoped to assemble 10,000 demonstrators in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> to blockade clinics from March 22-25.
</TEXT>
