<LOCATION> Maryville </LOCATION> lawyer, said he would not comment on the case. In in-vitro fertilization, the woman's ova are surgically removed and fertilized with sperm in a laboratory container, then implanted in the woman's womb in hopes of a pregnancy. <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> pioneered the practice and produced the world's first `` test-tube baby'' in 1978 Since then, other infertile couples have resorted to the method, which costs between $ 4,000 and $ 10,000 and has an approximately 15 percent success rate for each implant.
