<HEAD>Hijacked Plane's Steward Says Younis Pretended to Kill Guards</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A steward from a Jordanian jet hijacked in 1985 testified Friday that accused sky pirate <PERSON> Fawaz </PERSON> <PERSON> Younis </PERSON> threatened to kill passengers and crew and tricked them into believing his men had shot the plane's security guards. The steward, <PERSON> Omar </PERSON> <PERSON> Suliman </PERSON> <PERSON> El </PERSON> <PERSON> Ghadi </PERSON>, 32, was the fifth witness in the trial at <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> to identify <PERSON> Younis </PERSON> as the leader of five heavily armed men who stormed aboard <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jordanian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> flight 402 in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> on June 11, 1985. In the initial moments of the hijacking, <PERSON> El </PERSON> <PERSON> Ghadi </PERSON> testified, <PERSON> Younis </PERSON> ran to the front of the <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 727, pounded on the locked cockpit door with his gun and shouted, `` If you do n't open the door, I will explode it.'' The hijackers were armed with AK-47 assault rifles and hand grenades, according to testimony from other witnesses and a videotape taken at the end of the 30-hour ordeal. The testimony by <PERSON> El </PERSON> <PERSON> Ghadi </PERSON> was the first during the five-day trial to portray <PERSON> Younis </PERSON> as directly threatening the passengers and crew with death. <PERSON> Younis </PERSON>, 30, has pleaded innocent to a six-count indictment stemming from the hijacking. He was captured by <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agents in international waters in the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> more than two years after the hijacking, on Sept. 13, 1987, and the trial is seen as a test of a 1984 statute in which <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> authorities assert `` long-arm'' jurisdiction over the taking of American hostages abroad. Near the end of the hijacking, <PERSON> El </PERSON> <PERSON> Ghadi </PERSON> testified, the sky pirates told passengers and crew that at 7 a.m. the following morning, they would `` start killing'' them, `` the security officers first.'' The hijackers removed jewelry from a female security officer, and led all nine of them off the plane. `` We heard gunfire,'' testified <PERSON> El </PERSON> <PERSON> Ghadi </PERSON>. <PERSON> Younis </PERSON>, called Nazeeh by the other hijackers, came back aboard and said, `` That's it. We killed the security and put their bodies in the cargo of the airplane.'' The security officers were not, in fact killed, and <PERSON> El </PERSON> <PERSON> Ghadi </PERSON> said that when he saw them later in <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>, `` I was shocked.'' <PERSON> El </PERSON> <PERSON> Ghadi </PERSON> began his testimony by describing the early moments of the hijacking, as gunshots were heard outside the plane, passengers streamed inside, knocking the sky marshals off balance, and the hijackers ran aboard. The steward testified that he refused orders from the hijackers to close the door of the airplane for take-off, and that a few moments later, <PERSON> Younis </PERSON> emerged from the cockpit `` slapping and pushing'' the flight engineer to the rear to close the door. Another hijacker, called `` No. 2'' by <PERSON> El </PERSON> <PERSON> Ghadi </PERSON>, then began to beat the female security guard and threatened her with a knife. <PERSON> El </PERSON> <PERSON> Ghadi </PERSON> intervened. `` Hijacker No. 2 put his submachine gun at the back of my head'' and ordered him to search her, the steward testified. After refueling in <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>, the hijackers ordered the plane flown to <LOCATION> Tunis </LOCATION>, where they wanted to read a statement demanding that Palestinians be removed from <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. Tunisian authorities blocked the runways with trucks and the plane returned to <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. The sky marshals were taken off the plane, followed several hours later by the passengers and crew, most of whom shook hands with the <PERSON> Younis </PERSON> as they left. <PERSON> El </PERSON> <PERSON> Ghadi </PERSON> said he refused to shake hands and was again threatened with death but was allowed to board a bus with the other passengers and crew.
