 Racial tensions sparked when several white students waved <ORGANIZATION> Confederate </ORGANIZATION> flags during a black history program prompted officials to close classes for spring vacation two weeks early. `` We could tell this morning there was potential for disturbances and decided to dismiss,'' school Superintendent <PERSON> Kenny </PERSON> <PERSON> Goodwin </PERSON> said after students were sent home at 8:30 a.m. Friday. He said the week-long spring holiday would begin Monday instead of March 20 and `` will be a cooling off period.'' Authorities said no violence had been reported, but blacks had walked off the football and baseball teams at the 600-student high school and tensions were high. The problem developed Monday when several white students waved Confederate flags during a program for black history month at the high school. <PERSON> Goodwin </PERSON> said the five or six students who created the disturbance had been disciplined but not all had been suspended. In protest of Monday's incident, black athletes began a boycott of the football and baseball teams. Several black students interviewed after school Thursday said they dropped out of sports activities because they were `` hurt by what the white kids did.'' Some of the whites involved in the flag incident were members of the football team, said one black player who asked not to be identified. `` We've been playing with them all this time and then they do that. ... It hurt us,'' he said. The <ORGANIZATION> Oxford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eagle </ORGANIZATION> quoted sources close to the football and baseball teams as saying most of the players were boycotting at the request of their parents. One parent, who also asked not to be identified, said athletes would not return to the teams `` until we say they can.'' About 60 parents of black students met Thursday night with <PERSON> Goodwin </PERSON> and high school Principal <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Holt </PERSON> to discuss the problem.