<HEAD>Orders Down 1.3 Percent in January Due to Transportation Declines</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Orders to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> factories for manufactured goods declined 1.3 percent in January, reflecting a fallback in demand for transportation equipment from record levels a month earlier, the government reported Friday. Analysts said that despite the overall decline, the report provided evidence of continued strength in the economy. Excluding transportation, orders were up 0.2 percent in January after a 1.8 percent rise in December. The category of non-defense capital goods, viewed as a barometer of future industry investment plans, rose 1.6 percent in January to $ 40.1 billion. `` There may be a little more strength in investment than we had previously thought,'' said economist <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Hagens </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> WEFA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, a forecasting firm in <PERSON> Bala </PERSON> <PERSON> Cynwyd </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Pa </LOCATION>. Overall, orders for durable and non-durable manufactured goods fell to a seasonally adjusted $ 235.8 billion in January after posting a 4.7 percent increase in December, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reported. It was the first decline in factory orders since a 1.9 percent drop in September. The decline was attributed to a retreat in demand for ships, tanks and planes that resulted in an 8.5 percent decline in orders for transportation equipment last month. The category had surged 22.1 percent during the previous month to a record $ 39.6 billion. The motor vehicle, aircraft and shipbuilding industries all had posted large gains in December. Defense orders, subject to wide swings depending on when contracts are signed, plunged 33.9 percent in January to $ 6.9 billion after a 24 percent surge in December. Excluding the military, orders were up 0.2 percent in January after a 4 percent gain in December. Analysts expect economic growth to slow this year as the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> continues to tighten its grip on the money supply to cool the economy and dampen inflationary pressures. But most economic reports for January have signaled continued strength in the economy at the start of the new year. <PERSON> Irwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Kellner </PERSON>, chief economist for <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hanover </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, said January's factory orders figures were `` consistent with the feeling that the economy is still growing at a respectable rate.'' For all of 1988, orders for manufacturers' goods were up 9.7 percent, the best showing since 1979, after posting a 7.1 percent gain during 1987. American manufacturing was bolstered by strong demand for exports in the past two years as the decline in the value of the dollar against foreign currencies made <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> products more competitive in the international marketplace. In January, orders for `` big ticket'' durable goods _ items expected to last three years or longer _ were down 2.7 percent to a seasonally adjusted $ 128.5 billion. Demand for non-durable goods, meanwhile, was up 0.5 percent to $ 107.3 billion. Shipments of manufacturered goods were up 0.3 percent in January to a seasonally adjusted $ 231.6 billion.
