<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An oil slick was spotted today off sensitive marine reserves in the northern <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Keys </LOCATION>, but <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> officials said the spill did not appear to be a threat to the area. A flyover by <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> officials found the slick was 2 miles long and a quarter-mile wide, much smaller than first reported. `` It's not as bad as we feared,'' <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Dye </PERSON> said. Parks in the area reported small gobs of tar washing up, and said there did not appear to be major damage. <PERSON> Dye </PERSON> said dead birds were found out near the oil, but it was not clear if they were killed by the slick. A fisherman reported the oil just before 10 a.m., <PERSON> Dye </PERSON> said. `` We have no idea where it came from,'' he said. `` There are apparently no ships in the area.'' The Gulf Stream runs past Key Largo at that point, which means the oil could have come north from <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> or even farther away. The oil floated close to two sensitive north <LOCATION> Key </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Largo </LOCATION> marine reserves _ the <ORGANIZATION> Key </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Largo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sanctuary </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Pennekamp </PERSON> Coral Reef State Park. <PERSON> Pennekamp </PERSON> boasts the nation's only shallow-water living coral reef, which also extends into the federal Key Largo reserves. Coast Guard and park officials will consult to decide whether to order booms placed around the slick immediately and send boats to clean up the oil, <PERSON> Dye </PERSON> said. Although the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> said the spill was 10 to 12 miles offshore, there were reports of tar balls at the 120-square-mile Key Largo reserve, said park spokeswoman <PERSON> Maddy </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoover </PERSON>. `` We do n't know too much just yet, but we've gotten reports that we've got crude oil and tar balls from the size of baseballs to the size of grapefruit,'' she said. The 20-mile-long reserve stretches north from Molasses Point off the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> shore of Key Largo, and includes the area outside the 3-mile limit, while <PERSON> Pennekamp </PERSON> includes the shoreline and out to the 3-mile limit in some of the same areas, she said.
