 Government troops and workers ordered to abandon war-torn northern <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> to rebels, were stranded Friday for lack of transport, an African diplomat said. `` I understand it will take them a long time before they can return,'' the foreign envoy said in a telephone interview from <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>'s capital, <LOCATION> Addis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ababa </LOCATION>. If troops, civil servants and other officials abandon <LOCATION> Tigray </LOCATION> province, as ordered Monday by the government, that would leave the administration with no overland access to <LOCATION> Eritrea </LOCATION>, the extreme northern province that has the East African nation's only ports. The government still is flying planes into <LOCATION> Assab </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Massawa </LOCATION>, its main ports on the Red Sea. The retreat follows a series of rebel victories which the government referred to indirectly Thursday in a statement urging Ethiopians `` to be ready for an active involvement in every area of the armed struggle.'' `` No nation can tolerate violence, and there is no alternative now except to join hands and diffuse the aggression launched against the <LOCATION> Ethiopian </LOCATION> people,'' said the statement, published by the official <ORGANIZATION> Ethiopian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>. The diplomat, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said he did not know if rebels have moved into towns in northern <LOCATION> Tigray </LOCATION> province evacuated by the government. `` There are no government troops fighting there,'' he said. `` Even those who are left are in southern <LOCATION> Tigray </LOCATION>. There are no government officials in the north.'' The government did not refer directly to Tuesday reports by insurgents that the government had evacuated <PERSON> Tigray </PERSON>'s provincial capital, <ORGANIZATION> Mekele </ORGANIZATION>, `` fearing humiliating and shaking defeat as in <PERSON> Enda </PERSON> <PERSON> Selassie </PERSON> and surrounding areas.'' <PERSON> Enda </PERSON> <PERSON> Selassie </PERSON> is near <LOCATION> Mekele </LOCATION>, 475 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Addis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ababa </LOCATION>. `` The whole of <LOCATION> Tigray </LOCATION> is now liberated from the fascist regime of <LOCATION> Mengistu </LOCATION>,'' rebel spokesman <PERSON> Yemane </PERSON> <PERSON> Kidane </PERSON> told a reporter in <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>'s capital, <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION> The government said `` the secessionist <ORGANIZATION> TPLF </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Eritrean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> had coordinated attacks against Ethiopian army along <LOCATION> Adwa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Aksum </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Enda </PERSON> <PERSON> Selassie </PERSON> route with the view to dismember the <LOCATION> Ethiopian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Red </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> area from the rest of the country.'' <PERSON> Kidane </PERSON> said Tigrean rebels destroyed <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>'s 206th army corps, killing and wounding 14,645 soldiers and capturing 12,975, including a general. Rebel claims often are exaggerated and there was no way to verify <PERSON> Kidane </PERSON>'s statement. Early last year, Tigrean and Eritrean rebels in a joint offensive captured several towns, which the government retook in a midyear counteroffensive. Eritrean rebels have been fighting for independence since 1962 in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s oldest civil war. The Tigreans took up arms to demand more autonomy. <ORGANIZATION> Mengistu </ORGANIZATION> inherited the rebellion in 1974 when he and fellow officers overthrew the late Emperor <PERSON> Haile </PERSON> <PERSON> Selassie </PERSON> and established a Marxist government.
