<HEAD>Town Raises Money, Police Officers Recalled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MCKEESPORT, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Twenty-one laid-off police officers are being called back to work because a drive by residents, churches and businesses raised more than the $ 90,000 needed to pay them, the mayor of this strapped steel town said Friday. `` I'm overwhelmed by how the people opened up their hearts and pocketbooks,'' said Mayor <PERSON> Lou </PERSON> <PERSON> Washowich </PERSON>. `` We're a struggling community trying to make some type of economic recovery.'' Organizers of the drive to collect $ 90,000 said the total reached $ 94,000 by noon Friday. <PERSON> Washowich </PERSON> said the officers, nearly half the force, would return to work Sunday, one week after being laid off. `` This past week, while it's been very busy, the good Lord must have been watching us because we did n't have anything terrible happen,'' Police Chief <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brletic </PERSON> said. The mayor had asked all employees to take a wage freeze after the city discovered a $ 1.3 million deficit late last year, and he had said layoffs would result if the request was refused. <PERSON> Washowich </PERSON> ordered the police layoffs after a panel of state arbitrators awarded the police department 4 percent to 4 -LCB- percent pay raises. He said the city would save $ 90,000 by laying off the 21 officers for three months. Twenty-nine officers remained on the job. The city's volunteer ambulance company, <ORGANIZATION> McKeesport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Emergency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>, launched the fund-raising drive with a $ 15,000 donation. Residents dropped money into cans at churches, clubs, restaurants and businesses, and the ambulance company recorded the fund total each day on a cardboard thermometer posted at its station. The money includes the contributions of <ORGANIZATION> Equibank </ORGANIZATION>, which agreed to match every donation dollar for dollar. `` From the beginning I thought we would get the money, but I'm surprised we got it this quick,'' said <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Gregg </PERSON>, recording secretary of the ambulance company Funeral home owner <PERSON> Felix </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaworski </PERSON> donated $ 200. `` I just want to help our police force,'' he said. `` They do a lot for me here. We have a lot of vandalism around here and all I do is give them a call and they're on their way.'' <PERSON> Washowich </PERSON> said the success of the fundraiser wo n't solve the city's money problems and he has no idea how <LOCATION> McKeesport </LOCATION> will pay for the next year's police wage increase. `` I'm sorry to say the reality will set in,'' he said.
