 had fired his gun repeatedly. `` It is clear from the record that the present one-year sentence for this Class-D felony, which can have a maximum sentence of seven years, was imposed after careful and thoughtful consideration of the circumstances of the case and the subject's background,'' said the board's statement. <PERSON> Goetz </PERSON> began serving his sentence Jan. 13 after appeals in the state courts failed to reverse his conviction. On Monday, the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> also refused to reverse it. Had <PERSON> Goetz </PERSON> not appealed his conviction, he probably would have ended up serving considerably less time in jail. While upholding the conviction, state appeals courts also ruled that <PERSON> Goetz </PERSON> had been sentenced incorrectly. The trial judge had given him six months. At his court-ordered re-sentencing, <PERSON> Goetz </PERSON> was given the one-year term. <PERSON> Goetz </PERSON> is serving his sentence in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Rikers </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> jail, where he has been repairing radios for the police and fire departments. <PERSON> Elwin </PERSON> said <PERSON> Goetz </PERSON> got the standard treatment the parole board gives city jail inmates. One member, whom he would not identify, reviewed the prisoner's record and letters sent in by the judge, prosecutor and defense lawyers, <PERSON> Elwin </PERSON> said.
