<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prime Minister <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> announced political initiatives Friday to help heal the ethnic rift with rebellious Sikhs in the prosperous farming state of <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>, news reports said. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> said he will free most people detained in the 1984 army raid on the <ORGANIZATION> Golden </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION>; rescind legislation allowing detention without trial; and allow foreigners to travel around most of northwestern <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> state. Opposition and ruling party legislators, including some who support Sikh militants, loudly thumped their desks in a traditional expression of approval when <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> announced the initiatives in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> agency said. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> gave no time frame for the measures, Indian TV said. `` This is a step in the right direction. It is better late than never,'' said <PERSON> Sikhdev </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> <PERSON> Dhindsa </PERSON>, a former <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> state transport minister and member of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Akali </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dal </ORGANIZATION>, a Sikh party sympathetic to Sikh militants. <PERSON> Dhindsa </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> the measures would help solve ethnic strife that began in 1982 when Sikh militants began a bloody insurrection in demand of an independent homeland in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>. Referring to the release of the <LOCATION> Jodhpur </LOCATION> detenus, so called because most were detained in <LOCATION> Jodhpur </LOCATION> jail in <LOCATION> Rajasthan </LOCATION> state after the temple raid, <PERSON> Dhindsa </PERSON> said `` other innocent people in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> jails should also be released.'' Some 300 people were arrested in the Golden Temple complex during the 1984 army raid ordered by <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>'s mother, assassinated Prime Minister <PERSON> Indira </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>. Most were pilgrims held for questioning for complicity with Sikh militants who were holed up inside the temple complex. About 150 still are detained, many without charge. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> said all except those who face specific criminal charges will be released soon, <ORGANIZATION> UNI </ORGANIZATION> said. Foreigners will be permitted regular access to <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> and barred only from areas declared severely `` disturbed'' or overrun by militants, <ORGANIZATION> UNI </ORGANIZATION> quoted <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> as saying. Presently, all foreigners except accredited journalists need special permission to visit <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> also said he will rescind special provisions of the National Security Act allowing people in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> to be detained without charge for six months, <ORGANIZATION> UNI </ORGANIZATION> said. He told legislators the government also will curtail emergency powers given police under the Terrorist and Disruptive Activities Act, the news agency said. Village defense forces will be revived, <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> said, so people rely less on police for help against militants. Village-level elections will be held between May and September, <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> said, and committees based on the elections will supervise development work and law and order. Sikhs comprise less than 2 percent of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s population, but they are in a slight majority in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s agricultural boom state. Militant Sikhs claim they are discriminated against by a government dominated by the overwhelming Hindu majority, who are 82 percent of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s 880 million people. Militants wield enormous clout on the plea they are defending the Sikh religion from being swamped by <LOCATION> Hinduism </LOCATION>. Mrs. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> was shot and killed by two Sikh bodyguards to avenge the assault on the temple that is <LOCATION> Sikhism </LOCATION>'s most holy place. In 1988, the militants killed 2,400 people, mostly Hindus and moderate Sikhs opposed to their campaign for a separate homeland. <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> state legislature is suspended and the state is under President's Rule, administered directly by <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION>.
