<HEAD>Italians Deliver 1 Million Petitions to U.N. on Behalf of Condemned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A group opposed to the death penalty said Friday it gave <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> officials petitions with more than 1 million signatures denouncing such punishment and asking clemency for a woman on death row in <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Indiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> is considering an appeal of the murder conviction of <PERSON> Paula </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON>, 19, who is held at the <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Women </LOCATION>'s Prison in <LOCATION> Indianapolis </LOCATION> Ms. <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> was 15 in 1985 when she and three other teen-agers from <PERSON> Gary </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Ind. </LOCATION>, robbed and killed <PERSON> Ruth </PERSON> <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Pelke </PERSON>, a 78-year-old retired Bible teacher. Ms. <PERSON> Pelke </PERSON> was stabbed at least 30 times with a butcher knife. `` Thou Shalt Not Kill,'' an Italian anti-death penalty group, presented petitions with more than 1 million signatures appealing for mercy for Ms. <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> to <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> officials. Members of the group say they have also sent more than 2 million signatures gathered throughout <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> officials, including an appeal Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> issued in 1987. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> does not issue appeals for clemency in death penalty cases unless they involve political crimes or violations of human rights. The Italians conceded Ms. <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON>'s case did not fit those categories. Roman Catholics and some leftist groups in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> have adopted Ms. <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> as the figurehead of their campaign against capital punishment. <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> also have called for mercy. `` We're talking about a girl in the flower of her youth, in the prime of life,'' said <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Germano </PERSON> <PERSON> Greganti </PERSON>, the president of `` Thou Shalt Not Kill.'' `` In a sense, it's the defense of the ultimate person _ an adolescent, someone who needs the support of family and the political structure to complete her growth,'' said <PERSON> Greganti </PERSON>. <PERSON> Greganti </PERSON> also noted that Ms. <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> is black, `` and black people have been subject to a great deal of intolerence and discrimination.'' `` She has murdered someone,'' said <PERSON> Paolo </PERSON> <PERSON> Pietrosanti </PERSON>, another member of the group, `` but we also say that the most vile homicide is that which is perpetrated and premeditated by the largest number of people. `` This premeditated homicide itself is the death penalty,'' <PERSON> Pietrosanti </PERSON> said. Members of `` Thou Shalt Not Kill'' met with <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> for three hours in her <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> prison cell this week. When Ms. <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> was sentenced, <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> law allowed the death penalty for anyone over the age of 10 convicted of murder. The age limit has since been raised to 16, but was not made retroactive. As of Feb. 1, 27 people awaited execution in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> for crimes they committed before reaching age 18. Ms. <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> and <PERSON> Troy </PERSON> <PERSON> Dugar </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> are the only condemned prisoners who committed their crimes before age 16.
