<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Mayor <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON> ruled out halting new city building projects Friday in reaction to a <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling that voided <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>'s program to encourage minority-owned contractors. `` We will do what we have to do on a case-by-case basis without minority regulation,'' <PERSON> Young </PERSON> said. `` I hope we can continue to do business together.'' Young, a longtime civil rights leader, cited decades of slavery and segregation in likening the stricken <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> plan to the Marshall Plan that helped <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> back to its feet after World War II. `` We ca n't help but begin to see that the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> legacy has come home to roost,'' <PERSON> Young </PERSON> said. He said the <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> program, which set a goal of 35 percent minority participation in city contracts, had been aimed at `` full participation'' by all sectors of <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Young </PERSON> said at a news conference there was no need for a moratorium on contracts because most of the major projects he had planned in his nearly eight years in office already are under way. The <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled 7-0 Thursday that <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Minority-Female </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprise </ORGANIZATION> program was unconstitutional and that the city's defense of the 14-year-old program was `` woefully inadequate. It said there was insufficient evidence of past discrimination. <PERSON> Young </PERSON> said Friday that the guidelines were drawn and implemented `` in the implicit spirit of fairness'' to <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>'s black majority. <PERSON> Young </PERSON> sai