<HEAD>American Charged With Illegal Export of Engravings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DOMODOSSOLA, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An American has been charged by <LOCATION> Italian </LOCATION> customs police with trying to export ancient engravings and a fossil illegally, authorities said Friday. Dr. <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> <PERSON> Coulson </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Peoria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, did not try to hide the objects when he was checked by Italian border police on a train to <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>, said police Lt. Col. <PERSON> Umberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Selvaggi </PERSON>. `` He did not know that the objects were subject to artistic protection and could not be taken abroad,'' <PERSON> Selvaggi </PERSON> said. Police said the 46-year-old dentist bought the fish fossil and six engravings dating back to the 15th and 17th centuries in <LOCATION> Venice </LOCATION>. Authorities said they did not know the value of the objects. <PERSON> Coulson </PERSON>, who was stopped Feb. 25, was charged with trying to export objects subject to artistic protection, a crime that carries a maximum penalty of four months in jail and a fine based on the value of the objects. He was allowed to continue his journey and return to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.
