<SECOND>AM-Salvador-Mayors,0581</SECOND>
<HEAD>Half of Towns Without Mayors Because of Guerrilla Threats</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Half the country's 262 towns and cities were without mayors Friday, the result of a terror campaign by revolutionaries who say municipal chiefs administer <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> designs. `` Fear is human,'' said <PERSON> Armando </PERSON> <PERSON> Calderon </PERSON> <PERSON> Sol </PERSON>, mayor of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, in a recent interview with The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. `` They -LRB- other mayors -RRB- come to me for advice, but I ca n't ask them to be cannon fodder. They have their families to think about. I tell them it's a personal choice.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> says 131 mayors have chosen to resign. Some have been replaced by low-profile `` substitutes'' _ usually a member of the municipal council. Most have simply locked their doors, leaving residents no means of locally registering births and deaths, getting married or complaining about potholes. Marxist-led revolutionaries say mayors are a principal component of the `` U.S.-imposed counterinsurgency campaign.'' A 9-year-old civil war has killed an estimated 70,000 people. <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, a nation of 5 million, is the <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hemisphere </LOCATION>'s biggest recipient of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic and military aid _ about $ 1.5 million per day The rebels say <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>'s ruling class have sought, through elections, to put a democratic veneer on a state that remains dominated by the military. A big chunk of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid goes to development projects administered by the Salvadoran government through local authorities. Following municipal elections a year ago, the <ORGANIZATION> Farabundo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marti </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, or <ORGANIZATION> FMLN </ORGANIZATION>, began threatening mayors and insisting they announce their resignations. The guerrillas have assassinated nine mayors. The most recent slaying was in the eastern town of <LOCATION> Sesori </LOCATION> on Nov. 24. During the last two months of 1988, several municipal chiefs a week were taking to the air waves and buying newspaper ads to announce their resignations. At first, the guerrillas concentrated on their `` zones of control'' _ the northern sectors of <LOCATION> Chalatenango </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Morazan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Miguel </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Cabanab </LOCATION> provinces where they move freely and enjoy considerable support. But by late last year they were threatening mayors nationwide. Mayor <PERSON> Ricardo </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Miguel </LOCATION>, the nation's third-largest city, remains in his post despite two threats last month. `` I'm not challenging the insurgents to kill me,'' <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Leon </PERSON>, of the rightist <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION>, said in an interview. `` I do n't have enemies. I do n't even consider the left my enemy, because serving the people includes serving the left. But the people gave me this post, and only the people can tell me to leave it,'' he said. <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> asked the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> to arrange a meeting with local guerrilla leaders so he could ask them `` why I am considered a military target.'' He's still waiting to be contacted. `` Of course I'm afraid. But the support of the people gives me valor,'' he said. The campaign has been condemned by the <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> government, the armed forces, and even the Democratic Convergence, a guerrilla-allied leftist electoral front. The rebels, as part of a peace proposal, offered to stop the campaign if the government postponed presidential elections scheduled March 19 and met their demands for security and anti-fraud measures during the vote. The government and rebels have not been able to agree on when, where or how to negotiate on the proposal, which also ecompasses many other issues.
