<HEAD>Recruiting Irregularities Lead Marines To Tell 135 Recruits To Forget
It</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Marines have told 135 young people who signed up for the <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> but were not slated to report until later not to bother showing up, because their recruitments were fraudulent and they really were n't qualified, a spokesman said. Word of their release from the <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION>' delayed-entry program follows the dismissal of 30 recruits last month from boot camp at <LOCATION> Parris </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.C. </LOCATION> All the dismissals stem from the discovery that high school diplomas were fabricated and criminal and medical records were disregarded by the <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> recruiting station, said <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> spokesman Maj. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> McLean </PERSON> at <LOCATION> Parris </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>. Investigators concluded that recruiters signed up young men who were n't qualified in order to meet their recruitment quotas. Records of an additional 20 recruits in the delayed-entry program are being reviewed, he said Friday. <PERSON> McLean </PERSON> said earlier this week that Maj. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Eberhart </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, head of the <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> recruiting station, and 15 of his recruiters were relieved of duty and that two additional recruiters received administrative warnings because of the improper recruiting. In all, there are 47 recruiters assigned to <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>. None of the young men sent home from boot camp or released from the delayed-entry program faces any disciplinary charges, officials said. The actions follow an investigation triggered by a suburban <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> recruit's claim that his recruiter enlisted him even though he knew the young man had a severe stomach ulcer that should have disqualified him. The recruit had to be hospitalized while at boot camp. <PERSON> McLean </PERSON> said 30 recruits were sent home from boot camp after a review of 83 questionable cases. He told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday that in addition, 135 of nearly 700 recruits in the <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION>' delayed-enlistment program were also released `` over the same reasons that the others were disqualified for. The delayed-enlistment program allows recruits to commit themselves to the Corps without reporting to boot camp until up to six months later. Rep. <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> Walgren </PERSON>, D-Pa., said he met with the <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION>' congressional liaison and was told the <ORGANIZATION> Marines </ORGANIZATION> `` have never experienced this widespread a problem in their memory'' with fabricated `` This is a very high number of recruiters in a relatively small pool for them all to be involved in what is clearly a serious violation of rules,'' <PERSON> Walgren </PERSON> said. `` That number suggests they are under extraordinary pressure to produce, or it's something far widespread beyond this recruiting station.'' The head of the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> recruiting battalion in <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> said Thursday that a surprise inspection in November found six instances of possible improper recruiting. Four recruits were recommended for dismissal and two cases have not been resolved, said Col. <PERSON> Randell </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilkes </PERSON>.
