<HEAD>Perez Says Venezuela Has Suspended All Debt Payments</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to CORRECT that Perez not suspending debt payment
but saying whether debt payments can be made depends on austerity program;
no pickup</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NY4,NY5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIA TEJERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Andres </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> today said whether <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> can continue to make payments on its foreign debt depends on the success of its austerity program. `` The crisis Latin American nations are undergoing has a name written with capital letters _ foreign debt,'' <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> told foreign correspondents at <ORGANIZATION> Miraflores </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Palace </ORGANIZATION>, the government headquarters. A newspaper today reported more than 300 people died and and 1,500 were injured since Monday in riots in <LOCATION> Caracas </LOCATION> and 11 other cities. The unrest was caused by government-imposed bus fare increases, which appeared to release pent up frustration over the nation's austerity program. Buses and cars circulated in <LOCATION> Caracas </LOCATION> today as the capital returned to normal, with early morning traffic jams and honking horns replacing some of the tensions of this week's unrest. Looters emptied the shelves of supermarkets and neighborhood grocery stores in the first days of rioting. Since then, part of the 22,000 police and soldiers ordered on alert in <LOCATION> Caracas </LOCATION> have guarded stores, where people have been waiting hours in line to buy such staples as eggs, bread and cheese. <PERSON> Perez </PERSON>, in a morning news conference, said payments on the country's $ 33 million foreign debt depends on `` how our economic program develops.'' <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>, affluent during the 1970s thanks to its rich oil reserves, saw its fortunes slide along with petroleum prices in 1981. Real wages have since then fallen by a third, inflation is expected to double this year to 70 percent, and the $ 33 billion foreign debt is the fourth largest in <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> after <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> suspended payments on $ 20.4 billion of the debt in January, and the newspaper <ORGANIZATION> El </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nacional </ORGANIZATION> reported last week that payments on another $ 5 billion of the debt was suspended. Earlier this week, the government asked the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> to include provisions allowing <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> to suspend all payments on its debt until September. <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> also asked for an additional $ 4.3 billion in loans from the institution over the next three years. Asked if he intended to delay repayment beyond September, <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> said it would depend on the success of his economic adjustment program. <PERSON> Perez </PERSON>, who has been in office for only one month, has blamed leftists for prolonging <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>'s worst unrest in 31 years of <ORGANIZATION> democratic </ORGANIZATION> rule. On Wednesday, <PERSON> Gabriel </PERSON> <PERSON> Puerta </PERSON>, a former guerrilla leader, accused the government of inventing political motives for the disturbances, which he blamed on the failure of the government's economic policies. On Thursday evening, soldiers hunting snipers and seeking looters conducted house-to-house searches in downtown <LOCATION> Caracas </LOCATION> and the western slums. Shooting was heard early today as soldiers fired into the air and at buildings to flush out snipers. It appeared the gunfire also was meant to enforce the government's dusk-to-dawn curfew by keeping people off the streets. <ORGANIZATION> El </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nacional </ORGANIZATION> said in today's edition that more than 300 people had been killed and 1,500 injured in four days of violence _ the bloodiest in <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>'s history. Other reports said the death toll ranged from 250 to 350. The newspaper said its reporters counted 237 bodies at the <LOCATION> Caracas </LOCATION> central morgue and said there were other bodies in hospitals across the city. The dead included at least four children aged 3 to 14. <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> aide <PERSON> Reinaldo </PERSON> <PERSON> Figueredo </PERSON> said the government is setting up a food-distribution network with supplies airlifted from the rest of the country.
