<HEAD>Crew Describes Saving Flight 811</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto FX2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHLEEN MACLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The pilot who landed a jetliner after its side ripped open, ejecting nine passengers, said Friday that after the shock he said a quick prayer for his passengers and went back to work. Capt. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Cronin </PERSON> was in charge of <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> Flight 811 on its Feb. 24 non-stop flight from <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Auckland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION>, when shortly after takeoff the <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 747's right forward cargo door and an adjoining 10-by-10 foot section of fuselage tore away. In addition to the nine people missing, 27 were injured in the turbulence of the sudden decompression and the flight back to <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Cronin </PERSON> said the accident outweighed anything he experienced in the military as a fighter pilot. After realizing the extent of damage to the plane, `` I said a prayer for them -LRB- passengers -RRB- momentarily and got back to business,'' <PERSON> Cronin </PERSON> said at a news conference held within earshot of jets taking off and landing at <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>. First Officer <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Slader </PERSON> said simulated disaster exercises undertaken annually by <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> personnel were important but insufficient for the many problems that faced them. The crew `` reverted almost to survival instincts,'' <PERSON> Slader </PERSON> said. The crewmembers' answers were carefully controlled by airline officials, who prohibited them from answering questions pertaining to concerns about aging aircraft or the investigation of the disaster. <PERSON> Cronin </PERSON> was on his next-to-last flight, after 38 years of military and commercial flying and he said he's looking forward to his next _ and final _ flight. Because the flight took off through a fierce thunderstorm, he said he had ordered passengers to keep their seatbelts fastened. Without that precaution, many more lives would definitely have been lost, <PERSON> Cronin </PERSON> said. After the accident, the crew members said, they reached for oxygen masks but found the oxygen lines had been severed. <PERSON> Cronin </PERSON> said the plane was `` quivering and shuddering'' and he could see flames from one wing. During the 25-minute flight back to <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION>, the crew had to dump 90,000 pounds of fuel, partly because with only two engines the plane was, in effect, overloaded. In addition, the gaping hole in the side created drag which affected speed and control. Part of the emergency descent procedure for getting the plane back down to breathable air is to lower the landing gear to create drag. But <PERSON> Cronin </PERSON> said their decision not to lower the landing gear probably was critical to keeping the big jet from losing altitude too quickly before its remaining engines got it back to the <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION> runway. If they had lowered the wheels immediately, there `` would have been a good chance we would have gone in the water,'' he said. The crew also agreed to gradually move landing flaps to angles not normally prescribed to keep the plane in the air. `` I do n't think a 747 has ever flown on two engines at that weight. My concern for being overweight was staying airborne,'' the pilot told the <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday. Meanwhile, Second Officer <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> said he checked out the passenger area and saw `` no panic at all'' and that none of the passengers were moving. Normal landing speed with all four engines would have been 132 knots. The crew estimated that 170 knots would be safe. <PERSON> Cronin </PERSON> said he chose to touch down at 200 knots because he was afraid of losing control of the jet if he slowed it further. Once the plane reached view of <ORGANIZATION> Honolulu </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>, he said he was confident of the plane's safe landing, which took up two-thirds of the runway because of their speed and not having reverse thrust from all four engines. `` There was a sigh of relief and we started looking after the passengers,'' <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> said. After all remaining passengers had unloaded, <PERSON> Cronin </PERSON> said he and the other two crew members left by way of an emergency chute. They inspected the damage, which he described as `` a hole you could drive a semi-truck through.'' `` My reaction was, I ca n't tell you what my reaction was, like ` Oh, -LRB- pause -RRB- you know what. Oh, dear.'''
