<HEAD>Cerezo: Ortega ``Doesn't Like Democracy''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Guatemalan President <PERSON> Vinicio </PERSON> <PERSON> Cerezo </PERSON> said Friday political realities are pushing Nicaraguan President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> to abandon a `` totalitarian'' blueprint and pursue a democratic outcome for his country. <ORGANIZATION> Cerezo </ORGANIZATION>, who is here for talks with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration and congressional leaders, said <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> `` does n't like democracy. He's trying to make a revolution'' through a `` totalitarian'' formula At the same time, he said, <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> has had to pay attention to the demands of other Central American presidents that he embrace democracy, mindful that they would otherwise repudiate him. <ORGANIZATION> Cerezo </ORGANIZATION> spoke at a luncheon sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> Carnegie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Endowment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peace </ORGANIZATION>. Based on his discussions here, <ORGANIZATION> Cerezo </ORGANIZATION> said there are considerable doubts among <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration officials about <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON>'s willingness to comply with the <ORGANIZATION> democratic </ORGANIZATION> promises he made at the recent meeting of <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> presidents in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cerezo </ORGANIZATION> added that he believes these doubts are justified. The administration, he said, wants more assurances that democracy will be established in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> in a time period comparable to that of the demobilization of the Contras. Still, he said, he believes the administration is convinced that it should emphasize a diplomatic solution in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> rather than continuing to attempt to solve problems through military force. <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> spoke after administration and congressional officials disclosed details of the `` carrot and stick'' approach to <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> advocated by Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>. The policy includes unspecified rewards for <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> if it passes certain `` checkpoints'' on the road to democracy. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> made clear to lawmakers that he does not intend to abandon the Contra rebels, who now are subsisting on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> supplies in Honduran jungle camps along the Nicaraguan border. He told congressional officials he would seek to renew the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid, which runs out at the end of this month, for a year, according to some present at the Thursday meetings. Aid would continue to flow at current rates _ about $ 4 million a month _ and would keep the rebels available as a standby fighting force until after <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s national elections, which are being moved up to early 1990. At the Central American summit meeting, the five presidents agreed to try to draft a plan that would lead to the demobilization of the Contras in return for open elections in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> and the release of most of the 3,300 jailed Contras and former members of the armed forces who served under the <PERSON> Somoza </PERSON> family dynasty.
