<HEAD>NATO Outlines Conventional Arms Proposal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> will offer next week to trim key conventional weapons systems by 5 percent to 10 percent while asking the <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pact </ORGANIZATION> to make even larger cuts, an alliance source said Friday. The source, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the proposal for cuts in <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>'s main battle tanks, artillery and armored troop carriers would bring those weapons `` substantially beneath'' current levels. `` Since we are convinced that we ... -LRB- are -RRB- pretty much at the minimum of our defense this means for our military people a significant sacrifice,'' said the source, who outlined the plan to reporters at <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> headquarters. The plan also calls for <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact nations to slash by more than half their main battle tanks and artillery. The Western alliance contends the Soviets and their allies have built up a huge superiority in conventional, or non-nuclear, weapons in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. The alliance wants the East bloc nations to make much greater reductions in their forces to bring the two sides to rough equality. The proposal will be made Thursday when negotiators for the 16 alliance nations and the seven <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pact </ORGANIZATION> nations begin talks in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> on reducing conventional forces in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. The discussions will cover weapons in the vast region extending from the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> to the <LOCATION> Ural </LOCATION> mountains in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. The source said main battle tanks, armored troop carriers and artillery were singled out for initial discussion because they can be used in a surprise attack. He would only say <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> was prepared to reduce its holdings in tanks, artillery and armored troop carriers to 90 percent to 95 percent of current levels. The reduction, he said, ranges roughly between 5 percent to 10 percent. Under the <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> formula, an overall ceiling will be set of 40,000 main battle tanks _ 20,000 for each side. <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> said in a report last year that it has 16,424 such tanks in active units and an additional 5,800 in storage. It estimated the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact total at 51,500 with more than <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>'s in storage. The <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pact </ORGANIZATION>, in a recent count, put its tank total at 59,470 and <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>'s at 30,690. For artillery pieces, <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> will propose an overall cap of 33,000, or 16,500 for each side, according to the source. <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> estimated its artillery, which includes mortars and multiple rocket launchers, at 14,458 pieces plus an additional 2,870 held in storage. It estimated the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc's at 43,400 with more pieces in storage than that held by the West. The <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact count put its artillery at 71,560 pieces compared to 57,060 for the West. On armored troop carriers, the source said the alliance will suggest an overall limit of 55,000, or 27,500 for each side. It was unclear, though, how that would affect the actual count because neither <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> nor the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact has provided breakdowns for those forces. The <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> report said it has 4,153 armored infantry fighting vehicles plus 575 in storage, and that the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact has 22,400 with additional ones in storage. It also said the alliance has 35,351 other armored vehicles, including armored personnel carriers, and the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact has 71,000. The <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pact </ORGANIZATION> counts 70,330 infantry vehicles and armored personnel carriers for the East and 46,900 for the West.
