<HEAD>Britain Sentences Czechoslovak Spy To 10 Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Czechoslovak spy arrested last year while receiving secret radio messages from <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> was convicted of espionage on Friday and sentenced to 10 years in prison. <PERSON> Erwin </PERSON> <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> Haarlem </PERSON>, 43, whose real identity is still not known to police, posed as a Dutch art dealer and infiltrated Jewish groups while sending information back to his superiors, said the prosecution. It said he was an active agent here for 13 years. <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Haarlem </PERSON> pleaded innocent and was convicted by a jury after a five-day trial at the Old Bailey Central Criminal Court. Judge <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> recommended he be deported after serving his sentence. `` I have not the least doubt that you are a dedicated, disciplined and resourceful spy,'' <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Haarlem </PERSON> was recording a coded message when arrested at his north <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> apartment on April 2, 1988, by police from <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> Yard's special branch. Police seized six decoding guides hidden in a bar of soap, materials for `` secret writing'' and a list of locations for depositing and collecting material. Prosecutor <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Amlot </PERSON> told the jury that van <LOCATION> Haarlem </LOCATION> received 210 coded messages from <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> after arriving in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> in 1975. Among his assignments was to find out what firms were participating in proposed `` Star Wars'' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> space-based defense system, <PERSON> Amlot </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Haarlem </PERSON> joined Jewish organizations such as Conscience, a group devoted to helping Soviet Jews, and the Women's Campaign for Soviet Jewry. After his arrest, van <LOCATION> Haarlem </LOCATION> was taken to a police station where he asked for a message to be relayed to the Czechoslovak Embassy: `` <PERSON> Erwin </PERSON> <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> Haarlem </PERSON> has been arrested,'' said <PERSON> Amlot </PERSON>. This was done. The jury was told van <LOCATION> Haarlem </LOCATION> adopted the name of a Dutch child left by his mother in <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> after World War II. <PERSON> Amlot </PERSON> said the real van <LOCATION> Haarlem </LOCATION>'s mother searched for and found the Czechoslovak spy in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, and he pretended he was her son. Tests determined he could not have been her child, and she was told this. It was not clear what happened to the real van <LOCATION> Haarlem </LOCATION>.
