<HEAD>Group Proposes Havel For Nobel Peace Prize</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIOREL URMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>'s Charter 77 human rights movement has nominated jailed Czech playwright <PERSON> Vaclav </PERSON> <PERSON> Havel </PERSON> for the 1989 Nobel Peace Prize, an emigre source said Friday. The announcement came one day after 2,000 Hungarians said they would nominate <PERSON> Havel </PERSON> for the prize during a demonstration in <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION> seeking his freedom. Last month, two <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> congressmen had nominated the playwright, whose works are banned in his own country, for the prize. The London-based publisher <ORGANIZATION> Palach </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, which monitors events in <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>, said a Charter 77 committee would submit the organization's nomination to the Norwegian Nobel Committee in <LOCATION> Oslo </LOCATION>. The committee is made up of <LOCATION> Czechoslovak </LOCATION> activists, mainly intellectuals, in a bid to publicize the imprisoned dramatist's case and gain support for his nomination for the prestigious prize, <PERSON> Palach </PERSON> <PERSON> Press </PERSON> said. Sen. <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> DeConcini </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ariz </LOCATION>., and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Rep. <PERSON> Steny </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoyer </PERSON>, D-Md., also nominated <PERSON> Havel </PERSON> on Feb. 1 on behalf of the <ORGANIZATION> Helsinki </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, a human rights monitoring <PERSON> Havel </PERSON>, 52, was convicted last month on charges of incitement and obstructing police for his role in a January rally in <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION>, and he was sentenced to nine months in jail. The January rally honored <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Palach </PERSON>, a student who set himself afire to protest the Soviet-led invasion of <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> in 1968. <PERSON> Havel </PERSON>, who has appealed his sentence, had previou