<HEAD>Tower Appearance Would Set Senate Precedent</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Tower Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Tower </PERSON> could be the first Cabinet nominee ever to stand on the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> floor to answer questions from senators face-to-face, an ordeal that reporters were known to undergo during the 19th century. Senate Republican Leader <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> suggested the extraordinary appearance Friday to give the embattled nominee for <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary a chance to answer charges and questions about his personal life. Democratic leaders said they would consider any request. Associate Senate Historian <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Ritchie </PERSON> said no one has been called to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> floor for questioning in more than 50 years, and only five times that are listed in <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> records. Leaks of secret material to reporters were the target of early grillings on the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> floor and would be again if <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> gets his way. <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> suggested Friday that <ORGANIZATION> Tower </ORGANIZATION> needed a chance to rebut the allegations about his personal life that the Republican leader said were based on biased leaks from the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> report on Tower. The first recorded target of <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> questioning was <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Duane </PERSON>, editor of the <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aurora </LOCATION> newspaper. <PERSON> Ritchie </PERSON> said that <PERSON> Duane </PERSON> had written stories about secret <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> deliberations on changing the way electoral ballots were counted, stories based on leaks from senators. But <PERSON> Ritchie </PERSON> said <PERSON> Duane </PERSON> left the chamber to talk to his lawyer, fled the Capitol and never returned. Then in 1848 <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Nugent </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> was questioned about stories on secret <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> deliberations over a treaty. Thirteen years later, <PERSON> Zebulon </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON> and <PERSON> Hiram </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramsdale </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Tribune were hauled before the senators, again to be asked about leaks of secret treaty deliberations. `` No one revealed their sources,'' said <PERSON> Ritchie </PERSON>, adding that each of the three reporters was held hostage in <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> committee rooms to encourage them to cooperate. A more recent example _ cited by <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> _ came in 1933, when the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Sergeant-at-Arms <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> wrote a newspaper article some members found objectionable. `` Not all senators are crooks,'' <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> wrote, `` Just some of them.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> historian said that <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> was questioned on the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> floor that February, grilled later by a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> committee and then fired. Then in 1934, three airline officials were called to answer questions about government contracts with airmail carriers. As a former senator, Tower has the right to come to the floor of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, but does not normally have permission to speak to his one-time colleagues. Non-senators have spoken on the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> floor on other occasions, including lawyers defending those charged in impeachment proceedings. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> can, of course, allow anyone to speak to them by voting to do so.
