<SECOND>AM-Peru-Violence,0462</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebels Blamed for Butchering 39 Peasants in Peru</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AYACUCHO, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Shining Path guerrillas executed 37 men in a peasant village by cutting their throats, and shot to death a mother and her baby when the woman tried to flee, a military official said Friday. The attack Monday in a remote village was one of the bloodiest since the <ORGANIZATION> Shining </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Path </ORGANIZATION> launched its insurgency in <LOCATION> Ayacucho </LOCATION> state in May 1980. In a related matter, the government Friday prolonged for two months anti-rebel emergency measures in <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION> and parts of seven states where more than half of <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>'s 21 million people live. The measures suspend constitutional guarantees to travel and meet freely. They also permit government forces to conduct searches without a warrant and detain suspects for up to two weeks without filing charges. About 200 rebels in seven boats seized <LOCATION> Canaire </LOCATION>, a mountain hamlet located on the <LOCATION> Apurimac </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> 55 miles east of <LOCATION> Ayacucho </LOCATION>. The rebels surrounded villagers who had assembled in the central plaza, executed 37 men and shot to death a woman and her 9-month-old baby when she tried to flee, the official said. The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the violence was a revenge attack by the Maoist Shining Path guerrilla group. At the military's urging, <PERSON> Canaire </PERSON> had formed a peasant patrol against <ORGANIZATION> Shining </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Path </ORGANIZATION> attacks and members were gathering in the village plaza to make rounds when the guerrillas arrived, the official said. Many of the attackers wore army and police uniforms and took the peasants by surprise, he said. Villagers were confined in the village church after the executions, which they were forced to witness, he said. Since 1980 both rebels and the military have been accused of slaughtering peasant farmers in <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Andes </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountains </LOCATION>, mainly in impoverished <LOCATION> Ayacucho </LOCATION> state. In the largest massacre on record, guerrillas killed 87 peasants in 1983 in the village of <LOCATION> Lucanamarca </LOCATION>. In 1985, troops slaughtered 69 villagers in <LOCATION> Accomarca </LOCATION>. The Shining Path has systematically attacked villages that have organized peasant patrols under military orders to defend themselves against the rebels. Most peasant patrols are poorly armed with lances, slings and shotguns. The central and southern Andean highlands are populated by Quechua-speaking Indians who live in isolated hamlets. <LOCATION> Ayacucho </LOCATION>, the capital of <LOCATION> Ayacucho </LOCATION> state, is located 235 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION>. The region is the cradle of the <ORGANIZATION> Shining </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Path </ORGANIZATION> fight, which has claimed more than 12,000 lives. A state of emergency was first declared in <LOCATION> Ayacucho </LOCATION> in late 1982, and the measure has been prolonged periodically since. Other regions in the central highlands, the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> coast and the <LOCATION> Amazon </LOCATION> jungle were later declared emergency zones as insurgency spread.
