<HEAD>New Era in Reporting on Private Lives</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A panel of present and former <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> correspondents and former presidential press secretaries debated the limits of reporting on private lives of public officials Friday, with the <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Tower </PERSON> confirmation battle as a backdrop. The discussion took place during a symposium on the press and the presidency, sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> and the <PERSON> Lyndon </PERSON> <PERSON> Baines </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> <PERSON> Library </PERSON>. <PERSON> Eleanor </PERSON> <PERSON> Clift </PERSON>, who covered the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and now covers <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newsweek </ORGANIZATION>, said there was an `` audible gasp'' when Tower was asked at a <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> luncheon earlier this week whether he had ever violated his marriage vows. Tower, whose drinking habits and relations with women have dominated debate over his nomination to be secretary of <ORGANIZATION> defense </ORGANIZATION>, conceded he had done so, but said he did n't think he was alone. `` I think we all squirm a little when we get into these areas,'' Ms. <PERSON> Clift </PERSON> said. `` I think we all like to think there is a line beyond which we personally do n't go. I am uncomfortable. In the old days there was a clear rule. If it did n't interfere with the professional duties, it was n't news. Well, the line between private lives and professional duties is now so murky that almost anything spills over. So we do n't know where to draw the line.'' Although the discussion tounched on the Tower controversy, the question posed for the panelists was in the context of reporting about the private lives of presidents and their families. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Gerstenzang </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> said, `` If the president is performing in front of us, if it's something we are finding out, we are seeing or hearing about him, that's usable.'' <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Cormier </PERSON>, retired White House correspondent of The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, told the group that when he was covering President <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> aboard Air Force One, `` everything was off the record unless specified otherwise.'' `` It's very difficult for us in retrospect to realize how limited in a sense things were 25 years ago,'' <PERSON> Cormier </PERSON> said. In the <ORGANIZATION> Johnson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, he said, `` things got very fuzzy'' as to what was off the record. `` I guess they've gotten less fuzzy now,'' he said. `` I guess anything's fair game.'' <ORGANIZATION> Marianne </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hearst </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newspapers </ORGANIZATION> said reporters `` are tougher on ourselves today in all these personal areas, as we are tougher on our presidents.'' Ms. <PERSON> Means </PERSON> said that when she first came to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, `` people took free trips from people they were covering; the bottles of booze would arrive at Christmas.'' <PERSON> Sid </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> correspondent for NBC News, responded, `` It is true that journalists today do n't take tickets and booze and airplane rides, but I am not sure on the substance of stories that the standards are better today than they were 15 or 20 years ago.'' `` In the <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> era, we did hear stories about <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>'s private and social life, and those of us who covered <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> those days are often asked why we never put those stories on the air,'' <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> said. `` The reason why we never put them on the air is because all we heard was rumors.'' `` There are things that happened when we were correspondents that we did n't put on the air that would get on the air today or into print today,'' he added. <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Speakes </PERSON>, former spokesman for President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, said intense competition, spurred by the advent of 24-hour television, `` is driving the news to be stretched awfully thin at points. Reporters are having to come up with some new angle on a story where there may be no new angle.'' Ms. <PERSON> Means </PERSON> said that the more `` packaged'' a candidate or president become, the more `` sort of a cardboard person,'' the greater is the pressure on reporters to `` get behind that and see what the person is really like.'' `` That's where we get into areas that we used to consider strictly private,'' she said. <PERSON> Jody </PERSON> <PERSON> Powell </PERSON>, President <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>'s press secretary, said he was `` recoiling at the thought that the packaging of the candidates would suddenly cause us to begin writing about adultery. It seems to me that is not exactly why we are doing it.'' <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Warren </PERSON>, deputy press secretary to President <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>, said, `` The press, I think all of us, must live up to a little higher standard and I think when reports are floated around about elected officials, both in the executive branch and on the Hill, I think we should spend more time trying to prove or disprove those reports.'' <PERSON> Helen </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> bureau chief for <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>, said, `` All those candidates put out a press release every time they sneeze. They know that their life is going to be an open book.''
