<UNK>By STEVE ELLIOTT ^Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A fleet of tugboats and salvage ships worked in rough seas and gusty wind Friday to refloat a grounded tanker and stop any more of its cargo of 3.7 million gallons of crude oil from reaching <LOCATION> Oahu </LOCATION>'s beaches. Some of the 117,000 gallons of fuel and crude that spilled from the 800-foot tanker continued to leak and washed ashore along a one - to two-mile stretch of shore at Barbers Point on <LOCATION> Oahu </LOCATION>'s southwest coast, according to <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> Lt. <PERSON> Brad </PERSON> <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> Capt. <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Piche </PERSON>, commanding officer of the <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, said tugboat crews planned to try to free the ship at high tide at 2 a.m. Saturday. Crews were unloading ballast water Friday afternoon and preparing to remove some of the crude oil onto a barge, he said. Oil washed up on a beach where a popular tourist luau is held, prompting the state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> to post `` Polluted Waters'' signs, and at other areas as far as two miles to the north, said <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Hubbard </PERSON>. Helicopter crews determined the oil slick was not edging toward <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION>, said <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Santos </PERSON>. `` It's staying close to Barbers Point, and not drifting that much,'' <PERSON> Santos </PERSON> said. Tugboat crews reported Friday morning that no more oil was escaping from the <LOCATION> Exxon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, according to <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Alcantara </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION> attorney for <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> USA </LOCATION> The ship's 23 crewmembers were not injured and remained aboard, he said. The <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION>'s Pacific Area Strike Team was on its way from the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> with equipment to clean up the spill, <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> said. A local oil spill cleanup cooperative, called the <ORGANIZATION> Clean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Islands </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, was activated and on the scene, said <PERSON> Les </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON>, spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> USA </LOCATION>, the Houston-based domestic oil and gas division of <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> `` In addition, <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> has initiated response steps, including authorization of more tugs, if needed, to free the vessel,'' he said Elsewhere, an oil slick was spotted Friday off sensitive marine reserves in the northern <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Keys </LOCATION>, but <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> officials said the spill did not appear to be a threat to the area. Parks in the area reported small gobs of tar washing up, and said there did not appear to be major damage. Coast Guard spokesman <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Dye </PERSON> said dead birds were found out near the oil, but it was not clear if they were killed by the slick. `` We have no idea where it came from,'' he said. `` There are apparently no ships in the area.'' In <LOCATION> Antarctica </LOCATION>, the second oil spill in a month has been brought under control by Chilean navy personnel using chemical solvents to fight a kilometer-long slick created by a grounded Peruvian scientific ship, a Chilean navy spokesman said Friday. Leaks in two damaged tanks on the Humboldt were sealed by divers, he said. On Jan. 28, an Argentine navy ship, the <LOCATION> Bahia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paraiso </LOCATION>, ran aground off an <LOCATION> Antarctic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> peninsula </LOCATION> some 300 miles from the site of the Humboldt's accident, creating a major oil slick. It was eventually cleaned up by ships and personnel from <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> spill occurred Thursday evening about 15 miles from <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION>, but an <ORGANIZATION> Oahu </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said it was unlikely the oil would reach famed <LOCATION> Waikiki </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> to the east. `` The chances of that happening are very, very slim,'' said spokesman <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Apel </PERSON>. `` It's just too far away.'' There was no trace of oil along the shoreline beyond <LOCATION> Barbers </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Point </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> said, and there was no immediate move to close any beaches. There also was no evidence of affected marine life or seabirds being washed ashore, he said. Currents normally would carry the oil to the northwest away from <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION>, but gusty wind was blowing it in the opposite direction, he said. Nine tugboats worked to refloat the <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Houston </ORGANIZATION>, which broke free of its moorings and apparently drifted onto a reef during rough seas Thursday evening, <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> said. The ship's hull suffered minor damage, but was sitting in 16 feet of water and was in no danger of sinking, <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> said. `` We do know that one of the ship's fuel tanks and at least one of the empty cargo tanks have been breached,'' said <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON>. The vessel was three-tenths of mile off Barbers Point on <LOCATION> Oahu </LOCATION>'s southwest coast and had just unloaded 16.8 million gallons of <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Slope </LOCATION> crude oil to the Hawaiian Independent Refinery when it broke free of its moorings, <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> said The crew initially declined <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> assistance, but the ship's captain, <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Dick </PERSON>, later reported that the vessel was `` hard aground'' <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> said. An estimated 25,000 gallons of crude oil spilled when the tanker broke free during unloading, and 92,000 gallons of heavy bunker fuel oil spilled when an aft tank was ruptured when the tanker went aground, <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> said.
