<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Chilean couple who were denied political asylum in <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> tried to give away their five children Thursday by advertising for a foster home in a Norwegian newspaper. `` Is n't there a nice Norwegian family that wants to be parents to <PERSON> Oscar </PERSON>, 10, <PERSON> Luis </PERSON>, 6, <PERSON> Nicolas </PERSON>, 4, <PERSON> Natalia </PERSON>, 2, and <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON>, three months?'' asked the couple in the Faedrelandsvennen newspaper in the southern town of <LOCATION> Kristiansand </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Patricio </PERSON> <PERSON> Arrancibia </PERSON> <PERSON> Collao </PERSON> and his wife <PERSON> Raquel </PERSON> <PERSON> Quesada </PERSON> <PERSON> Molina </PERSON> took the painful step because they feared their children would be killed or disappear if they returned to <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>, the national news agency <ORGANIZATION> NTB </ORGANIZATION> reported. `` This is the first time we've seen anything like this,'' said <PERSON> Tove </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnsen </PERSON>, manager of the <ORGANIZATION> Kristiansand </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Immigrants </ORGANIZATION>' Office. `` I consider it very serious that a family has reacted so strongly to a rejection that they would give their children up for adoption rather than take them out of the country,'' she told the news service. The couple's attorney, <PERSON> Sverre </PERSON> <PERSON> Nordmo </PERSON>, told <ORGANIZATION> NTB </ORGANIZATION> they still can appeal their deportation order by April 6, and that he was surprised when they took such desperate action. When he arrived here in March 1988, <PERSON> Collao </PERSON> told officials he had been tortured in a Chilean prison in late 1987. His family followed him to <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> the following month, <ORGANIZATION> NTB </ORGANIZATION> said. Most of the 900 or so Chileans who arrived during the first half of 1988 risk being deported because Norwegian authorities believe they would be in no real danger in their homeland, according to the Norwegian <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION>. By the latest count from the state <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Statistics </ORGANIZATION> there were 3,747 Chileans living in <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> in July 1988.
