<BYLINE>Six Charged in `Business of Death' ^By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Six leaders of a violent, multimillion-dollar crack ring were charged Thursday with nine murders and seven attempted murders, officials said. The defendants, all from <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION>, were in `` the business of death,'' said District Attorney <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Holtzman </PERSON>. `` These gang members allegedly killed not only members of rival drug gangs but tried to enforce their writ by killing their own employees to enforce discipline.'' The leaders also were accused of murdering three innocent bystanders in the course of operating the multimillion-dollar crack ring, <PERSON> Holtzman </PERSON> said. `` I think we got one of the major gangs,'' said <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> Chief of Detectives, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Colangelo </PERSON>. `` There are several others but none have its scope and violence.'' A 70-count indictment charged the six men with enterprise corruption under the state's version of the federal racketeering statute. They also face numerous counts of murder, attempted murder, assault, weapons and drug charges. The crimes outlined in the indictment occurred between June 1987 and last month. If convicted, the defendants would face up to life in prison. The drug ring had about 50 members and six retail locations in east <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> that each brought in $ 10,000 to $ 25,000 daily, officials said. `` The group was particularly callous in terms of sellin to youths,'' said <PERSON> Colangelo </PERSON>, who noted that two of the locations were near public schools. The gang's alleged leader was identified as <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Edmonson </PERSON>, 28, who was on parole for a robbery conviction. The other defendants are <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Amante </PERSON>, 31; <PERSON> Kyle </PERSON> <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON>, 24; <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Breland </PERSON>, 32; <PERSON> Winston </PERSON> <PERSON> Easterling </PERSON>, 19; and <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>, 28. <PERSON> Edmonson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Amante </PERSON> were arrested Wednesday and the other four were arrested earlier, officials said. In addition to the arrests, authorities seized $ 106,000 in cash, various guns, more than 400 vials of crack, the highly addictive cocaine derivative, and three ounces of cocaine, <PERSON> Holtzman </PERSON> said.
