<HEAD>Judge: Evidence Enough to Try Contra Supporter In Drug Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARLOS A. SANDI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A judge ruled Thursday there is sufficient evidence to try U.S.-born <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Hull </PERSON> for drug trafficking and violating <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rican </LOCATION> security by providing arms to Nicaraguan rebels. Judge <PERSON> Maximo </PERSON> <PERSON> Esquivel </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> tribunal in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carlos </LOCATION> would not say what evidence he used to make his decision. The judge said evidence indicates that between 1982 and 1986, <PERSON> Hull </PERSON> worked with a Costa Rican citizen to provide arms to Nicaraguan rebels, known as the Contras, in their guerrilla war against the lefist Nicaraguan government. A trial date has not been set. <PERSON> Hull </PERSON> will be tried in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carlos </LOCATION>, about 105 miles northwest of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jose </LOCATION>, because the crimes allegedly were committed in that jurisdiction. <PERSON> Hull </PERSON>, 69, a former <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> resident, has lived in <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION> for 20 years. He has said he became a Costa Rican citizen eight years ago. <PERSON> Hull </PERSON> has acknowledged supporting the Contras and has said that in the past he let them use his property in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Chiles </LOCATION>, 81 miles northwest of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jose </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Hull </PERSON> was been in custody since Jan. 13, when he was arrested by Costa Rican authorities. Since Feb. 14 he has been jailed in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carlos </LOCATION> after spending time in a hospital for heart problems. Sources in the Office of Judicial Investigations have said they acted after residents near <PERSON> Hull </PERSON>'s farm on the Nicaraguan border denounced activities by him that were seen as possibly endangering relations between <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Hull </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> Rita </PERSON> <PERSON> Herrera </PERSON>, said Thursday said she would appeal the judge's ruling. She and other defense attorneys have tried unsuccessfully to have <PERSON> Hull </PERSON> released on bail. The 4th District Court in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jose </LOCATION> provisionally set bail at $ 12,500, but the superior court tribunal in <LOCATION> Alejuela </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Province </LOCATION>, where the trial was later moved, denied bail because of the severity of the charges. <PERSON> Herrera </PERSON> has argued that <PERSON> Hull </PERSON>'s arrest was politically motivated. <PERSON> Hull </PERSON> in the past has strongly denied any connection to drug trafficking. Witnesses testifying before <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on illegal arms shipments to the Contras said <PERSON> Hull </PERSON>'s ranch was a way station for gun smugglers and cocaine traffickers. <PERSON> Hull </PERSON> was among 29 people named in a civil suit filed last year by two journalists. <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Avirgan </PERSON> filed the suit with his wife, <PERSON> Martha </PERSON> <PERSON> Honey </PERSON>, after being wounded in a 1984 news conference bombing blamed on the defendants. A <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> district juddge in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> ruled in favor of the defendants, saying the plaintiffs failed to prove their contention that a conspiracy was behind the bombing. Eight people were killed in the bombing and the apparent target, then-Contra leader <PERSON> Eden </PERSON> <PERSON> Pastora </PERSON>, was wounded.
