<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> plan to cut imports of Iranian oil, officials said Thursday, but neither depicted the move as being in reaction to a death threat against novelist <PERSON> Salman </PERSON> <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON> by <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruhollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> A French oil company official, however, said the French decision was linked to worsening relations with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> after <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s revolutionary and religious patriarch, attacked <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON> over his book `` The Satanic Verses. Many Moslems find the book blasphemous. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s cutback will be up to 20 percent over the next three months. Officials in the trade and foreign ministryies said it was because of a seasonal decline in demand and not motivated by the <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON> affair. `` It's true that there will be a decline in coming months but it has nothing to do with political issues,'' said <PERSON> Tsukasa </PERSON> <PERSON> Kawada </PERSON>, deputy director of the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>'s Energy Resources Division. In <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, an <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said oil companies were urged to slacken imports about 10 days ago. While <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> issued no formal directive on cutting oil imports, a senior official from the <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>'s hydrocarbons service `` suggested'' to French oil companies that they trim imports following <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>'s death threats against <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON>, according to industry sources speaking on condition of anonymity. The suggestion was not overtly linked to the <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON> matter. Officials suggested only that a high level of imports was `` inappropriate'' at this time. But one official at a major <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> oil company said, `` It was suggested to us it would be inappropriate for us to increase our imports of Iranian crude, or to maintain them at a high level, in the present diplomatic context.'' <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>'s call on Feb. 14 for Moslems to kill <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON> provoked some economic backlash in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, notably <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. All member nations of the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> recalled their ambassadors from <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> condemned the death edict but did not withdraw its ambassador. So far this year, Japanese purchases of Iranian crude averaged about 300,000 barrels a day, greater than in previous months because of the larger winter demand. Purchases are likely to drop to 240,000-250 ,000 barrels in the second quarter, oil company officials say Last year, Iranian oil accounted for 5.7 percent of total Japanese oil imports, a drop of 18.3 percent from 1987.
