<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> mortality rates for two of the three leading causes of death _ heart disease and stroke _ are headed downward, but cancer is on the increase as unhealthy habits of yesteryear catch up with the older population. The <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> death rate from heart disease in 1987 was 313 per 100,000 people, down from 318 the year before. For stroke, or cerebrovascular disease, the rate was 61 per 100,000, down from 62. But the mortality rate from cancer, the nation's No. 2 killer, has been going up in recent years, the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> said. There were 196 cancer deaths in 1987 for every 100,000 Americans, up from 195 the year before.
