<HEAD>With PM-Eastern, Bjt</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Here is a look at <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, which is facing a strike by its Machinists at 12:01 a.m. EST Saturday unless negotiators reach an unexpected breakthrough in a 17-month-old contract dispute.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Owner: The 60-year-old airline has been owned by <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, headed by Chairman <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>, since 1986. Headquarters: <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>. Employees: 31,200, including 8,500 members of the <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> union, which includes mechanics, bag handlers and other ground workers; 3,500 pilots and 5,900 flight attendants. Size of fleet: 250 jets. Cities served: 118, with its major markets in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. Number of flights: 1,040 daily. Passengers: 100,000 average daily. Main strike issues: <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>, which claims it lost $ 1 billion in the past decade and is losing more than $ 1 million a day, is seeking $ 150 million in wage concessions. The Machinists are seeking $ 50 million in raises. Where negotiations stand: The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mediation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> is trying to get both sides to reach a settlement before the strike deadline. The board has asked President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to appoint an emergency panel that could delay the strike 60 days. The White House said Thursday that no decision had been made. In the event of a strike: Eastern has vowed to continue flying, although company officials refuse to divulge contingency plans. The company promised passengers would be rerouted or given refunds on any canceled flights. The Machinists have threatened to picket other airlines, ships and railroads, and <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION> officials have said they want their 14 million members to support the <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZAT