<HEAD>Lorenzo, Bryan Head Opposite Sides</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> showdown pits one of the airline industry's most feared bosses against a union leader who may be the industry's most stubborn. <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. Chairman <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>, 48, is a <LOCATION> Queens </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, son of <LOCATION> Spanish </LOCATION> immigrants, <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> graduate and aggressive builder of the nation's largest airline company He's had no success dealing with <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> union District 100 President <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON>, 55, a West Virginia-born mechanic and magnetic, self-educated man who says he takes his strategies from Zen, the Bible, <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>, <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> and the ancient Chinese author <PERSON> Sun-tzu </PERSON>'s `` The Art of War.'' With a <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> union strike deadline set for midnight EST Friday, about the only point the two driven men agree on is that Eastern may not survive a strike. <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> bought Eastern three years ago with a warning that `` there ai n't no <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Claus </LOCATION>,'' and his new management sent <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s usually tense labor relations plummeting to new lows with wage concession demands, toughened work rules and thousands of layoffs, firings and suspensions. His Eastern management has added to a union-busting reputation he gained when he ended a labor confrontation at <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> in 1983 by taking the carrier into bankruptcy reorganization and getting union contracts abrogated. <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> has outraged Eastern unions by taking over <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s computerized reservations system, collecting tens of millions of dollars in `` management fees'' and loans from <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>, and agreeing to sell <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s profitable and prestigious Northeast shuttle service to developer <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> That $ 365 million sale is not final. Management says it has tried to work with <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON>, but that the union leader wants to run the airline himself. A booklet titled `` Charlie Says ...'' put out recently by <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> warns: `` If <PERSON> Charlie </PERSON> is n't stopped, he will destroy Eastern.'' Former Eastern chairman <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Borman </PERSON> says <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> has `` a certifiably insane dream'' of running the airline himself, and <PERSON> Borman </PERSON> recently compared <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> to cult leader <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, who led a mass suicide of followers in <LOCATION> Guyana </LOCATION> in 1978. <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON>, elected president of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s largest union in 1980 and overwhelmingly re-elected twice, got <PERSON> Borman </PERSON> to back down and give pay increases in 1983 on the last day of a <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> strike deadline. In 1986, with Eastern facing bankruptcy, <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> refused to join the pilots and flight attendants in making wage concessions unless they were tied to <PERSON> Borman </PERSON>'s ouster. Eastern's board of directors refused, and sold the company to <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>, who built tiny, money-losing <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> into the Houston-based <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> that took over <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Frontier </ORGANIZATION> and other small carriers. <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>, who initially indicated he would n't involve himself in <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s labor situation, ignored a post-sale telegram from <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> asking for a meeting. But last year, as negotiations with the <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> stalemated and <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> unions fought management with myriad lawsuits and political lobbying, <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> had dinner with <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>. The dinner only led to more disputes and <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> continued to hope for a buyout of Eastern. <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> contends that Eastern has been badly mismanaged for years at the employees' expense, and that workers would increase productivity and service with more input into how the company is run. Corporate kingpins <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON>, <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Boone </PERSON> <PERSON> Pickens </PERSON> and <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> have all been approached by <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> unions about buying <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>, but <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>, which has posted record losses since taking over the airline, has said there are no buyers on the horizon. <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON>, a mechanic since 1956 at an airline whose last strike was in 1966, has seen his union rolls reduced from 12,000 to 8,500 since the <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> takeover. `` Our people have been frustrated, there have been attempts to provoke wildcat strikes,'' <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> said recently. `` They have been brutalized by management that does n't care about the company's future. While promising `` a wing-ding of a strike,'' <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> also worried that the company may not survive. `` We've fought them as long as we could and we've had some success,'' he said. `` Unfortunately, our system does n't seem to look out for the working man.'' <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>, meanwhile, made a last-ditch personal appeal to <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> pilots this week. In a videotape showing a shirt-sleeved <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> in a homey easy chair, he urged: `` Eastern is either going to make it through this period, make the changes that are necessary and go on and succeed ... or I'm afraid <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> is going to go through this juncture and perhaps end up in the corporate graveyard.''
