<HEAD>Europe To Urge U.S. To Amend Computer Reservations System</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Western European aviation officials have urged <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to end a built-in bias against European air carriers in the five computerized reservation systems used by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airlines and travel agents. These systems are programmed to favor <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> carriers though European airlines fly the same routes to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and in much less time, the European officials said Thursday. `` Consumers suffer from not always being given ready access to the best -LRB- flight -RRB- information,'' by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> computerized reservation systems, <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Hudson </PERSON>, secretary of the 22-nation <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION>, told reporters. Representatives of the two biggest <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> computerized reservation services, Apollo and <ORGANIZATION> Sabre </ORGANIZATION>, said the criticism came at a time when they were taking steps to correct the situation. `` I'm surprised that they would be saying this now with all the things that have happened in the recent past,'' said <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> Cook </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>' Sabre system. Since December, <ORGANIZATION> Sabre </ORGANIZATION> has offered travel agents two ways of displaying flight information, one of which is more favorable to European airlines, Ms. <PERSON> Cook </PERSON> said. Apollo plans to offer two display options starting later this month, according to <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> McIntyre </PERSON>, director of products marketing for <ORGANIZATION> Covia </ORGANIZATION>, the parent of Apollo. The European accusations echo accusations by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airlines that <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION> discriminated against other carriers with their reservation systems. Since 1984 the <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> has required the systems not to give any preferential treatment. <PERSON> Hudson </PERSON> said he would raise the issue in a meeting with <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> officials this month. To date, `` There has been a marked reluctance from the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government to open its ears to what has been said by the Europeans,'' he added. Reservations made through <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> computerized reservation systems often involve `` unnecessarily lengthy journey times with long overlays at connecting points'' because the computers favor <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> carriers, <PERSON> Hudson </PERSON> said. He said they list <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> carriers on the first screen while flights of European carriers are tucked away on remote screens that booking agents do not check unless travellers say at what hour they want to leave. The five <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> systems are known as Apollo, <ORGANIZATION> Sabre </ORGANIZATION>, Pars, Datas-II and System One. <PERSON> Hudson </PERSON> said none gives priority to flights to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> where warranted. As an example, he cited a non-stop <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco-to-Paris </LOCATION> flight on <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> UTA </ORGANIZATION> airline that he said is up to 5 -LCB- hours faster than flights on major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> carriers that make stopovers. Yet Sabre puts the <ORGANIZATION> UTA </ORGANIZATION> flight on screen 9 rather than on the first screen, he said. Flights of <LOCATION> Air </LOCATION> <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Lufthansa </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Alitalia </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> SAS </ORGANIZATION> get similar treatment though they get travelers from <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> hours faster than <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> carriers, he said. <PERSON> Hudson </PERSON> said the 22 <ORGANIZATION> ECAC </ORGANIZATION> nations will issue next week rules of conduct for <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s two main computerized reservation systems, Amadeus and <ORGANIZATION> Galileo </ORGANIZATION>. These rules, he said, give non-European carriers first-screen priority if their flights are more convenient. He called on the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government to do likewise.
