<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Rakolta </PERSON> won a skirmish and now she wants to start a battle against what she says are sexually oriented and violent programs that cut into the network television fare her children can watch. `` The American family is beng painted into a corner. It's an invasion of my privacy at this point,'' <PERSON> Rakolta </PERSON> said Thursday. A flurry of letters starting in January brought <PERSON> Rakolta </PERSON> apologies from advertisers on the top-rated, prime-time `` Married ... With Children'' program. Some pulled their ads on the <ORGANIZATION> Fox </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> series. <PERSON> Rakolta </PERSON> said Thursday she objects to having to monitor prime-time television for shows she does n't want her younger children to watch. `` If people want that stuff, they can pay for it, or rent it, or go to the movies,'' she said. <PERSON> Rakolta </PERSON> said she intends to start a group, or join existing ones, to organize national boycotts of advertisers. `` One person can really make a difference if they push the right buttons. And the right buttons are not the producers in <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION>, they're the people that pay the money for the show,'' she said. The activism is new, said <PERSON> Rakolta </PERSON>, 40, who lives in affluent <LOCATION> Bloomfield </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION> in suburban <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>. She has daughters ages 18, 10 and 9, and a son, 8. Her husband, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Rakolta </PERSON>, is president of a large construction company. `` I've never been involved in a cause. I've been involved in civic groups, but nothing cause-oriented,'' she said. But she said that when she and her children watched `` Married ... With Children'' one Sunday night in January, she ended up shooing the children out of the room. The situation comedy, which began in 1987 and is <PERSON> Fox </PERSON>'s most successful show, is about a blue-collar family headed by shoe-store clerk <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Bundy </PERSON>. <PERSON> Rakolta </PERSON> said the first show she saw featured a man's visit to a lingerie store `` In the store, one woman removed her bra for strangers, asking how she looked. It showed a man that worked there, an older man, walking around in a garter belt. They mentioned vibrators on the show,'' <PERSON> Rakolta </PERSON> said. `` I was thinking it was a family program because it was prime time, 8:30 p.m. I was horrified. I wanted to know what kind of sponsors would sponsor a show like this,'' she said. <PERSON> Rakolta </PERSON> said she watched other episodes to see who advertised. On one, she said, the father asked his children, with his wife standing nearby, what women and `` dog do do'' have in common, and told them, `` They get easier to pick up as they get older.'' Since <PERSON> Rakolta </PERSON> wrote them, <ORGANIZATION> Procter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gamble </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> McDonald </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Kimberly-Clark </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Tambrands </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> have told their advertising agencies not to buy time on the program. The president of <ORGANIZATION> Coca-Cola </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Ira </PERSON> <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON>, said his company will screen future episodes more closely. `` I must tell you that I am corporately, professionally, and personally embarrassed that one of our commercials appeared in this particularly unsuitable program episode,'' <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> wrote <PERSON> Rakolta </PERSON>. Fox officials defended the show. The <PER