<HEAD>Whittle Reports No Advertiser Defections From TV News Project</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The architect of a plan to send commercials along with a news show into classrooms says advertisers backing a test run of the program are standing firm despite growing criticism of the proposal. <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Whittle </PERSON>, head of <ORGANIZATION> Whittle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> LP </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Knoxville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, said eight sponsors have signed contracts to buy 80 percent of the commercial time available during the test that starts Monday. `` No one who has signed has even called and said they were worried,'' he said Thursday in response to reports that a second major education group has gone on record opposing commercials in school. Whittle refused to identify the eight sponsors, saying it would become evident who they are once the test run starts in six schools on March 6. As part of the test, <LOCATION> Whittle </LOCATION> has equipped six schools with about $ 50,000 each in television monitors, recording equipment and sattellite dishes so they can receive the 12-minute daily news show he is producing for teen-agers. The schools, in exchange, are to run the show each school day. The show, called Channel One, will include two minutes of paid commercials. The advertising has outraged some educators, who say big business should not be allowed that kind of access to the classroom. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parent-Teacher </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday that its 22-member executive committee opposed sending commercials into the schools. Earlier this week, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Secondary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Principals </ORGANIZATION> voted to urge principals to avoid programs that have commercials. <ORGANIZATION> Levi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Strauss </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, the San Francisco-based apparel maker, is one of the sponsors of the test, but <PERSON> Levi </PERSON>'s marketing manager, <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Chew </PERSON>, said the uproar has n't prompted the company to reconsider its support. `` We are very sensitive to the public debate and we are monitoring it and listening as closely as anyone else,'' he said. But he said that public reaction to the idea of including ads on a news show for schools is only one issue on `` a long list of criteria'' for making a decision on whether to continue advertising on the show if Whittle proceeds with plans to make it available next year in 8,000 schools. <PERSON> Whittle </PERSON> said many schools would not be able to afford a topical, daily news program like he is producing or the hardware. He says allowing two minutes of commercials is a reasonable way to finance it. He said his company has made presentations to 15 advertisers seeking their support for the program and that only three, whom he declined to identify, have declined. In addition to the eight that signed contracts, he said he is continuing negotations with four others and is hopeful that two of three of them will buy the remaining commercial inventory. <PERSON> Lou </PERSON> <PERSON> Nagy </PERSON>, spokesman for sneaker maker <ORGANIZATION> Converse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Reading </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, said Converse is n't interested in being a sponsor, though it counts on the teen-age consumers that Whittle is courting. `` Our feeling is that there are plenty of opportunities to reach the teen-age audience and we just feel that doing it in the classroom is maybe overdoing it a little bit,'' he said. In another development Thursday, <PERSON> Whittle </PERSON> said it had reached an agreement to send non-sponsored programming to the test schools from the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountain </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Network </LOCATION>, which represents public television stations in 13 western states. An unspecified number of programs will be delivered over the same satellite system that carries the Channel One program, and schools are free to use the shows as they choose. Whittle already publishes a number of magazines and sponsored posters that are distributed in schools across the country, and he notes that the advertising in those publications has not come under fire. But critics say a sponsored television show that is being shown in classrooms will be more difficult than other media for students to ignore.
