<SECOND>PM-Ad Backlash, Bjt,0798</SECOND>
<HEAD>Racy TV Show Loses Several Major Advertisers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The defection of several advertisers from the television comedy `` Married ... With Children'' highlights concern among image-conscious corporations over TV's increasingly racy fare, some industry insiders said. Two major advertisers quit buying time on the <ORGANIZATION> Fox </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> situation comedy. Others have spurned selected episodes for fear the show's frank language and references to sex would offend viewers, executives of the advertisers said Thursday. Advertising already is tough to find for `` tabloid TV'' programs such as `` Geraldo'' that delve into kinky sex, devil worship and similarly salacious subjects, advertising executives say. Some defectors from `` Married,'' which is the fledgling <PERSON> Fox </PERSON>'s top-rated show, were influenced by an energetic letter-writing campaign by a Detroit-area mother, <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Rakolta </PERSON>, spokesmen said The show, about a blue-collar family named <PERSON> Bundy </PERSON>, features references to sex and bathroom humor, buxom women and frequent portrayals of the husband berating his wife. Two advertisers, <ORGANIZATION> Procter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gamble </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Products </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, bought some ads on the show but have decided against further sponsorship, spokesmen said Thursday. <ORGANIZATION> Johnson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> McDonald </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> officials said they had decided against running national advertising on the show, though individual, locally purchased ads for the two had run. <ORGANIZATION> Coca-Cola </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION>, whose president, <PERSON> Ira </PERSON> <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON>, wrote an apology to Mrs. <PERSON> Rakolta </PERSON>, continues to screen `` Married'' episodes for content, but has n't found one suitable for advertising since her complaint Jan. 15, said spokesman <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Tortorici </PERSON>. Advertisers' concerns were summed up by <ORGANIZATION> Procter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Gamble </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON> <PERSON> Gillespie </PERSON>: `` We felt that the whole theme of the show is basically one we do not want to be associated with. We were concerned about the negative portrayal of American family life.'' <PERSON> Fox </PERSON>, which purposefully appeals to the young adult audiences advertisers covet in its efforts to build a fourth television network, has n't had any trouble selling ads on the show, which is broadcast Sunday evenings, said spokesman <PERSON> Brad </PERSON> <PERSON> Turell </PERSON>. `` The show is completely sold out,'' he said, adding that news reports of Mrs. <PERSON> Rakolta </PERSON>'s campaign prompted calls of support from viewers. `` We have received literally hundreds of telephone calls today from across the country from viewers saying that this one woman's opinion is getting too much attention and hoping that we wo n't change the show,'' <PERSON> Turell </PERSON> <ORGANIZATION> Procter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Gamble </ORGANIZATION>, which makes hundreds of household products, bought ads on several `` Married'' episodes last year, stopped from October through December then sponsored two shows in January, Ms. <PERSON> Gillespie </PERSON> said. After receiving Mrs. <PERSON> Rakolta </PERSON>'s letter, officials reviewed the show and decided against further ads, she said. American Home Products, which makes goods ranging from Jiffy Pop to Woolite, had already decided to disassociate itself from the show before receiving Mrs. <PERSON> Rakolta </PERSON>'s letter, said spokeswoman <PERSON> Carol </PERSON> <PERSON> Emerling </PERSON> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Tambrands </ORGANIZATION>, which produces feminine hygiene products such as Tampax, planned to advertise on two `` Married'' episodes but canceled the second after a review prompted by Mrs. <PERSON> Rakolta </PERSON>'s letters, said <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Konney </PERSON>, a spokesman in the company's <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> headquarters Advertisers face a dilemma in deciding whether to sponsor racy shows, which often attract big audiences but may offend some vocal consumers. So-called tabloid TV shows like `` Geraldo'' have difficulty attracting advertisers because of what many see as their exploitation of the weaker side of humanity. A recent survey of advertisers and ad buyers found resistance to such shows, topped by the often-outrageous `` The <PERSON> Morton </PERSON> <PERSON> Downey </PERSON> Jr.'' talk show, said <PERSON> Dean </PERSON> <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON>, vice president of <PERSON> Harrington </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Righter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Parsons </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> firm that helps television stations sell air time. Virtually all big companies have guidelines for what kind of shows are acceptable for their ads, and most hire screening companies to check shows in advance for problems. As television presses the outer limits of taste _ boosted by more lenient federal regulations and greater competition for ads with other media _ finding an appropriate spot for an ad be difficult, said McDonald's spokeswoman <PERSON> Stephanie </PERSON> <PERSON> Skurdy </PERSON>. `` Ours is a children's and family business,'' Ms. <PERSON> Skurdy </PERSON> said from the company's <LOCATION> Oak </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Brook </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, headquarters. `` It has become increasingly difficult to find family programming on prime-time television.'' But <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Isaacson </PERSON>, vice president of <ORGANIZATION> Young </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rubicam </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> advertising agency, said complaints about shows' content did n't appear any more frequent now than they ever have Those who seek to influence television content through pressure on advertisers are attempting censorship, said <PERSON> Carol </PERSON> <PERSON> Sobel </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> attorney. `` If you do n't want to watch it then do n't watch it,'' Ms. <PERSON> Sobel </PERSON> said. `` I think what is inappropriate is to force your views on anyone else.''
