<FIRST>r f PM-RetailSales     03-03 0741</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Retail Sales,0765</SECOND>
<HEAD>Higher Rates To Restrain Spending But Retailers Unlikely To Suffer
Soon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Economists say rising interest rates have started to influence people's spending decisions, but purchases of clothing and other everday items will be among the last things affected. There was no evidence of a slowdown in consumer spending in reports Thursday from the nation's largest retailers, which showed many of them enjoyed healthy sales gains in February. A continuing turnaround in women's apparel and renewed demand for other consumer and household goods contributed to last month's gains for department stores, discount chains and general merchandise vendors. Retail sales measure important aspects of consumer spending activity, which accounts for about two-thirds of all <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic activity. <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Kudlow </PERSON>, chief economist at the investment banking firm <ORGANIZATION> Bear </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stearns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, said the recent rise in interest rates, partly reflecting the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>'s effort to squeeze inflationary pressures, may be changing people's minds about spending. `` I think we are already in the early stages of a slowdown in consumer spending,'' <PERSON> Kudlow </PERSON> said. `` You are seeing a higher savings rate, which is the flip side of slower spending.'' Higher interest rates will have the most impact on purchases typically financed over time, such as cars and home appliances. <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Feiner </PERSON>, a retail industry analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, said the effect on sales of clothing and routine items will be much more limited. `` We still remain relatively sanguine about the retailing outlook, given the improvement in women's apparel as well as our belief that retailers will maintain very strong control over inventories and expenses,'' he said. For many of the retailers, February marked the start of their 1989 financial year. Balance sheets showed signs of improvement last year, analysts said, due largely to unexpectedly brisk business before and after Christmas. February typically is a low-volume month as merchants prepare for a seasonal shopping pickup in the spring. But analysts detected favorable omens in the latest tallies. One good sign was stronger sales of apparel, apparently because women are finding the latest styles more appealing than last year's fashions <ORGANIZATION> Limited </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the apparel retailer, said sales rose 22 percent in the four weeks ended Feb. 25 from the year before and sales at stores open at least a year _ called same-store sales _ went up by 19 percent. Retailers and industry analysts say same-store sales give a more accurate reading of a company's performance than totals that include sales at newly opened stores. Not every retailer reports same-store sales. At <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Roebuck </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's largest retailer, sales of sporting goods, toys and auto accessories posted strong gains, said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Bozic </PERSON>, chairman and chief executive officer of <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Merchandise </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION>, which on Wednesday inaugurated a new low-pricing policy at all of its more than 800 stores, said sales for the four weeks ended Feb. 25 went up 13.2 percent from the year-earlier level and same-store sales rose 6.6 percent. K mart Chairman and Chief Executive <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonini </PERSON> said sales of small appliances, home electronics and items in its pharmacy division contributed to overall sales growth. K mart's sales for the four weeks ended Feb. 22 grew 8.3 percent and sales at stores open a year or more were up by 3.5 percent. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Howell </PERSON>, chairman of <ORGANIZATION> J.C. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Penney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said promotions for Valentine's Day and President's Day boosted sales, particularly for men's merchandise and home furnishings <PERSON> Penney </PERSON> said sales in the four weeks ended Feb. 25 increased 5.3 percent and same-store sales gained 2.5 percent. The company has discontinued lines such as home electronics, some sporting goods and photographic equipment over the year and, excluding those lines, sales for February rose 9.8 percent. Among other retailers reporting Thursday: <ORGANIZATION> Wal-Mart </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the fast-growing discount and general merchandise chain based in <LOCATION> Bentonville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ark. </LOCATION>, recorded a 25 percent sales rise in February. Same-store sales rose 11 percent. Minneapolis-based <ORGANIZATION> Dayton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hudson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said sales for the four weeks ended Feb. 25 were up 11 percent over the year and same-store sales rose 4.7 percent. The results reported Thursday were from most of the biggest general merchandise chains and apparel retailers, excluding <ORGANIZATION> Campeau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> R.H. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Macy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Batus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which do not release monthly figures. Unlike monthly retail sales figures released by the federal government, they do not include sales at auto dealers, supermarkets or restaurants.
