<HEAD>Dollar Steady, Gold Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar held against most major currencies today, though some traders believed its recent rally was running out of steam. Gold prices rose. One trader in <LOCATION> Milan </LOCATION> said the dollar's room for upward movement is limited by the continued worries about the health of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy. `` There are still too many fundamentals that are weak in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION>,'' the trader said. Nonetheless, `` I'm not going to be selling dollars soon.'' Another trader in <LOCATION> Milan </LOCATION> said that if the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> rejects President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s choice of <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Tower </PERSON> as secretary of <ORGANIZATION> defense </ORGANIZATION>, the dollar would likely lose ground. `` The market generally likes a strong American president. But if Tower's candidacy fails, the ` wimp factor' will re-emerge,'' the trader said. The pound sank in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to $ 1.7205 from $ 1.7270 late Thursday. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where trading ends before <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s business day begins, the dollar rose 0.05 Japanese yen to a closing 128.12 yen. Later, in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it was quoted at 128.00 yen. Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Thursday's rates, included: 1.8443 West German marks, up from 1.8405; 1.5775 Swiss francs, up from 1.5710; 6.2740 French francs, up from 6.2575; 2.0831 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0735; 1,357.50 Italian lire, down from 1,360.50; 1.1935 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1945 Gold opened in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid price of $ 384.30 a troy ounce, up from $ 383.75 bid late Thursday. At midmorning, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $ 386.50. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, gold was trading at $ 386.50 at noon, compared with $ 383.25 late Thursday. Earlier, in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold rose 86 cents an ounce to close at a bid $ 386.75. Gold dealers in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> said the market appeared to be ignoring the dollar, while the metal gained strength from some short covering and buying interest out of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>. Silver bullion rose in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to a bid price of $ 5.80 a troy ounce, up from $ 5.76 late Thursday.
