<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar held its ground against the Japanese yen at the end of trading today, while share prices toppled sharply from earlier highs to finish the week marginally lower. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar finished at 128.12 yen, up only 0.05 yen from Thursday's 128.07 close. It had started trading at 128.58 yen and moved mainly between 128.10-128 .70 yen during the day Dealers said the dollar was mainly supported by a West German decision Thursday not to change its interest rates. <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION>, the West German central bank, said it would maintain its discount rate and its Lombard interest rate at 4.0 percent and 6.0 percent, respectively. `` Because of the announcement, the dollar managed to touch 128.70 yen during the morning session, but fell back in afternoon trading,'' said a dealer with a major Japanese securities firm. He said a speech by Bank of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Satoshi </PERSON> <PERSON> Sumita </PERSON> in the afternoon erased gains made by the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency, causing it to drop to 128.12 yen. In the speech to businessmen, <PERSON> Sumita </PERSON> said the domestic price situation is becoming `` more severe'' when compared to last year, and that it was important to act `` promptly and flexibly'' to deter inflationary fear. `` Market participants took that to mean <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> may hike its own interest rates,'' the dealer said, speaking on condition of anonymity. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s discount rate presently stands at 2.5 percent, the lowest among major industrialized countries. On the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> index also fell from earlier gains to close the week marginally lower at 32,000.10 points, down 73.63 points, or 0.22 percent. It had started trading with a strong 226.34-point gain, but