<FIRST>r f PM-EmployeeBenefits Bjt   03-03 0701</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Employee Benefits, Bjt,0720</SECOND>
<HEAD>IRS Softening Health Plan Anti-Discrimination Rule</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> is temporarily softening the sting of a new law affecting the group health insurance of many American workers, but opponents say the only solution is repeal. A bill to kill the law, which requires businesses to demonstrate that their health plans do not discriminate in favor of upper-income employees, has been signed by 183 members of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>. Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> LaFalce </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Small </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, says he expects a majority of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> _ 218 members _ to have signed his repeal bill within a few weeks. One employee-benefits consultant estimates that almost half the nation's companies with more than 1,000 workers can not say with certainty that their plans do not discriminate. The Internal Revenue Service on Thursday issued 220 pages of regulations explaining to employers how they could comply with the law, which is known as Section 89. The law was enacted as part of the big tax overhaul of 1986 and amended as recently as last November. Although the law took effect Jan. 1, the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> said employers need take no action to comply with it before July 1. In addition, a good-faith effort to comply will be treated by the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> as having satisfied the law at least until next Jan. 1. Business representatives said the regulations do nothing to make th law more attractive `` Section 89 represents a major attack on our employee benefit system,'' said <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> Berg </PERSON>, human-resources manager for the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION>. `` In reality, it's a back-door effort to tax employee benefits. The length and complexity of the regulations make it clear that Section 89 should be repealed.'' `` It is obvious that they have failed to provide understandable guidance for Section 89,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Sloan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> enacted Section 89 in an effort to extend health insurance to more workers. The provision requires employers to apply complex mathematical tests to their benefits packages to prove that they are not biased against workers making less than $ 50,000 a year. Many businesses complain that the law, by weighting them down with paperwork, could have the opposite effect by encouraging abandonment of employee health insurance. Treasury and <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> officials say their discussions with accountants indicate most businesses will have no major problem complying with the law. In large part, that assumption reflects that the general principles applying to health and welfare benefits are similar to those that have governed employee pensions since 1974. The regulations announced Thursday, on which the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> will take comments until May 8, apply chiefly to health insurance, since that is the benefit affecting most employers. However, the transition rules, including the date changes, also apply to term life insurance. Under the law, before an employer's benefit plan can be considered qualified by the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION>, it must be written, enforceable, permanent and maintained exclusively for the benefit of workers. If a plan is not qualified, all employees pay tax on the benefit. A second set of requirements is designed to prevent the plan from being overly beneficial to higher-income workers. If an employer's plan fails this test, only the highly paid employees _ not rank-and-file workers _ would have to pay tax on the value of the excess insurance coverage In explaining the regulations, the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> scoffed at a story repeated often by opponents of Section 89. This story holds that a hypothetical $ 20,000-a-year janitor whose $ 150,000 heart surgery is covered by insurance would have to pay tax on the full $ 150,000 if his employer's health plan failed to meet qualification rules. `` That result is not reached under these regulations,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> McGovern </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> assistant chief counsel. The regulations state that if a plan does not qualify, a worker making under $ 50,001 would be liable for tax on only 10 percent of medical expenses that were reimbursed under the insurance plan. The percentage would rise with income; a worker earning over $ 150,000 would pay tax on the full reimbursement. The <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> said no penalty would be imposed for a small violation that was corrected within 90 days.
</TEXT>
