 houses operating at the exchange would be sychronized with the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>'s floor clock, ensuring greater uniformity in time-stamping trades. In another development, both the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Merc </ORGANIZATION> have asked member traders not to respond to a Wall Street Journal survey requesting opinions on the federal probe. <ORGANIZATION> Merc </ORGANIZATION> officials sent out a five-page letter urging members to beware of the `` deviously phrased'' survey. The letter also cites `` defects'' in 10 of the survey's 12 questions that <ORGANIZATION> Merc </ORGANIZATION> officials said are calculated to produce a `` distorted story.'' Board of Trade officials, meanwhile, told members that any survey responses `` may undermine our efforts to reinforce investor confidence in the integrity of our markets.'' The survey asked traders for their opinions on <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> tactics, on whether there was cheating at the exchanges and to what extent, and the effectiveness of internal disciplinary actions. A spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, publisher of the Journal called the survey a `` standard reporting technique.''
