<HEAD>Mood is Anxious at Eastern Terminals, in Air</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Eastern Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Stands for MIAMI-dated Aboard Eastern on AM Business News Digest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The anxiety of passengers and <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> employees was evident Friday at <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> terminals and in the air as the midnight deadline loomed for a strike against the ailing carrier. Operations seemed to be running normally at <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s terminal at <LOCATION> LaGuardia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and there was no evidence of additional police presence Friday morning. But bitter employees were vocal about <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> management and pessimistic about the prospects for a last-minute settlement of the dispute between <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> and its Machinists union. `` There's tremendous anger'' at <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>, the chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s parent <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, said a male flight attendant onboard an early morning run from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>. `` I would rather see the airline burn to the ground'' than have it continue under current management, said the employee from <LOCATION> Queens </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, who has worked for Eastern for 11 years. The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York-Miami </ORGANIZATION> flight, which had been overbooked, was delayed nearly an hour while flight attendants offered free round-trip tickets on Eastern to passengers willing to give up their seats. There were few takers, but precious minutes went by as the gamblers left the aircraft and seats were found for the passengers replacing them. At the terminal, Florida-bound passengers worried about getting back to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> quizzed ticket agents _ some of whom, at least, seemed to be making an extra effort to be courteous and upbeat. The check-in lines were fairly long but orderly and fast-moving. <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> `` is in a class by himself,'' said one agent, who reported she had been besieged by questions from passengers. She expressed optimism, though, that an 11th-hour settlement could be reached to avert a strike, as happened in 1986 when former <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> chairman <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Borman </PERSON> sold the airline to <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>. Some passengers joked about the hardship of not being able to get back to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> when temperatures in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> were running at around 80 degrees. But others were anxious. A young woman on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York-Miami </ORGANIZATION> flight, due to take another <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> flight from <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Juan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>, on Saturday was worried that she and the 190-member tour group she was escorting would n't make it. `` If the pilots go on strike -LRB- with the <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> -RRB-, this airline is finished,'' she said. `` I'd hate to see another <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> company go under; I would rather see their prices go up than a company go under.'' An <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> pilot riding `` jump seat'' on the flight _ not working but transiting to his next assignment _ insisted that a Machinists' strike against <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> ca n't be effective without the support of the pilots The pilots union at <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> has balloted its members, but the results have n't yet been announced. `` I do n't think -LRB- Eastern management -RRB- has run the airline very well,'' the 10-year pilot said.
