<HEAD>Laura Ashley Says U.S. Retailer Copying Its Goods</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Laura </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ashley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Holdings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> Friday charged <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> retailer <ORGANIZATION> Limited </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> with copying the bottles and packaging design of perfumes sold by a <PERSON> Laura </PERSON> <PERSON> Ashley </PERSON> subsidiary. A suit filed in federal court in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> by <PERSON> Laura </PERSON> <PERSON> Ashley </PERSON> and its <ORGANIZATION> Penhaligon </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary seeks to stop <PERSON> Victoria </PERSON>'s Secret shops owned by Limited from selling perfumes in bottles and packaging designs that allegedly are direct copies of ones used by <PERSON> Penhaligon </PERSON>'s. The complaint says Limited and <PERSON> Victoria </PERSON>'s Secret produced the knock-off line after they were unsuccessful in their attempts to acquire <PERSON> Penhaligon </PERSON>'s. Besides seeking to stop the manufacture and sale of the perfumes, <PERSON> Laura </PERSON> <PERSON> Ashley </PERSON> is seeking an unspecified amount in monetary damages. A statement from <PERSON> Laura </PERSON> <PERSON> Ashley </PERSON>, which is a British company that sells women's fashions, fabrics and some home furnishings, said the suit was filed as a claim of unfair competition under the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trademark law and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> state law. <PERSON> Laura </PERSON> <PERSON> Ashley </PERSON> has been expanding its <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> presence in recent years. <PERSON> Penhaligon </PERSON>'s, also based in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, has been in business since the 1870s as a perfume retailer and was acquired by <PERSON> Laura </PERSON> <PERSON> Ashley </PERSON> in 1987. Its fragrance products are sold in about a dozen <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> department stores and to over 2,500 mail order customers. The statement said <PERSON> Leslie </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wexner </PERSON>, Limited's chairman, is one of the mail order customers. <PERSON> Penhaligon </PERSON>'s perfumes come in glass-stoppered bottles with an unusual shape. The company has been awarded Royal Warrants from the Duke of <LOCATION> Edinburgh </LOCATION> and the Prince of <LOCATION> Wales </LOCATION> and its perfume packaging bears seals to reflect the endorsements. The suit claims Limited and <PERSON> Victoria </PERSON>'s Secret have tried to simulate the Royal Warrant on their perfume packaging.
