<FIRST>r f AM-SEC-Auditors     03-03 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SEC-Auditors,0356</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rule Change Approved</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> approved rule changes Thursday designed to give investors faster notice when corporate auditors turn up fraud or other irregularities. Under the previous rules, a company had up to 15 days to report the resignation of its auditor in a dispute and an additional 30 days after that to make public a letter from the auditor outlining the disagreement. The new rule, approved on a 4-0 vote, requires companies to report the resignation of an auditor within five days and to file the auditor's letter with the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> within 10 days, thus tightening up the disclosure period from 45 days to 15 days. The changes come more than a year after members of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> complained about the rule during a January 1988 hearing on the notorious ZZZZ Best fraud case. <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Minkow </PERSON>, a teenage <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> financial wizard, parlayed a rug-cleaning business based in his parents' garage into a multimillion-dollar, publicly traded corporation. <ORGANIZATION> ZZZZ </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Best </ORGANIZATION>'s independent auditor, <ORGANIZATION> Ernst </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Whinney </ORGANIZATION>, discovered irregularities and resigned on June 2, 1986. But, the firm's suspicions were n't made public until July 16, 1986 In the meantime, unwitting investors continued to buy <ORGANIZATION> ZZZZ </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Best </ORGANIZATION> stock, which became worthless. Rep. <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyden </PERSON>, D-Ore., had been pressing for even faster disclosure of irregularities turned up by accountants, by requiring the accountants to go directly to the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> with their suspicions But, <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruder </PERSON> told <PERSON> Wyden </PERSON> at a hearing last year the commission lacked the power to require reports directly from auditors. <PERSON> Ruder </PERSON> said he would support a change in the law giving the commission that power. The commission plans to publish its new rules within several weeks. They would become effective 30 days after that. <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> member <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Fleischman </PERSON> expressed concern that the tightened deadline would create a burden on firms, but the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> staff said there had been only about a half dozen cases within the past six months that would have been affected.
</TEXT>
