<HEAD>Supply Fears Fuel 5-Day Copper Rally</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Persistent supply concerns pushed copper futures prices sharply higher Friday on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, capping a weeklong rally that boosted copper by more than 10 percent. On other exchanges, precious metals also advanced; energy futures retreated; pork bellies plummeted, leading livestock futures lower; and grains and soybeans were mixed. Copper settled 2.4 cents to 5.6 cents higher with the most active contract, for delivery in May, at $ 1.437 a pound. The spot March contract finished at $ 1.53 a pound compared with the spot settlement price of $ 1.386 a pound a week earlier. Prices rose despite an apparent reduction in tensions between Peruvian copper miners and the government. In <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>, the world's sixth-largest copper-producing nation, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> continued plans for a 3-day `` warning strike'' beginning March 26. The miners contend the government has not honored the agreement that ended a 57-day strike late last year. The union said Friday it was willing to accept some compromises in the interim before the strike, although workers did not rule out possibly extending the strike beyond three days. Copper's underlying supply-and-demand factors remained overwhelmingly bullish, with near-term availability extremely limited going into the second quarter, historically a period of heavy consumption. `` We have a convergence of the technical, fundamental and seasonal factors,'' said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Neill </PERSON>, research director with <ORGANIZATION> Elders </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` This is an extremely positive period for the market.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> reported that copper supplies deliverable against the March contract increased by 113 tons Thursday to 17,446 tons. But analysts said copper stocks are so low that the increase had scant market impact. Precious-metals futures prices rose amid fears that a strike in the industrial-metals section of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Rustenburg </LOCATION> mining complex could spread to the platinum sector. <LOCATION> Rustenburg </LOCATION> is the world's largest platinum mine. A drop in the dollar's value against other major currencies also contributed to the rise in precious metal values, analysts said. Platinum settled $ 5.40 to $ 5.60 higher on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> with April at $ 539.30 a troy ounce. On the <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, gold settled $ 2.70 to $ 3.20 higher with April at $ 389.30 a troy ounce; silver was 3.9 cents to 4.8 cents higher with March at $ 5.801 a troy ounce. Energy futures traded higher for most of the session on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Merc </ORGANIZATION> but finished lower after a late wave of profit-taking that erased nearly half of the previous day's strong gains in the crude oil market. West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 16 cents to 22 cents lower with April at $ 18.56 a barrel; heating oil was .59 cent to 1.07 cents lower with April at 50.80 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .36 cent to .72 cent lower with April at 51.53 cents a gallon. Heavy profit-taking in the pork belly market led the decline in livestock and meat futures prices on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. The March belly contract plummeted 2 cents a pound, the maximum daily price change permitted by the exchange. Live cattle settled .20 cent to .55 cent lower with April at 77.80 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .45 cent lower with March at 82.42 cents a pound; live hogs were .40 cent lower to .08 cent higher with April at 44.15 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were 2 cents lower to .48 cent higher with March at 37.25 cents a pound. Wheat, oats and soybean futures prices settled mostly lower on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> but corn finished mixed in response to a lower-than-expected forecast for Argentine corn production. Most of the selling was triggered by profit-taking the soybean market, which soared to a 4-week high on Thursday. Wheat settled 1 -LCB- cents to 3 -LCB- cents lower with March at $ 4.32 -RCB- a bushel; corn was 1 cent lower to 2 -RCB- cents higher with March at $ 2.78 \ a bushel; oats were 2 -LCB- cents to 4 cents lower with March at $ 2.05 -LCB- a bushel; soybeans were 8 cents lower to -LCB- cent higher with March at $ 7.67 -RCB- a bushel
