<HEAD>Court Rules Against Atlanta's Minority-Female Business Enterprise
Program ^Eds: SUBS 6th graf, `An employee ..., with 3 grafs comment from
city officials, Young news conference slated; picks up 7th graf: `Among
those ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The city's affirmative action-minority enterprise program was overturned Thursday by the state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, which said officials failed to produce enough evidence of past discrimination to justify it. The court also unanimously found that the <ORGANIZATION> Minority-Female </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprise </ORGANIZATION> program, begun in 1975, was too broadly drawn and failed to consider alternatives to a yearly minority participation goal in city contracting. The program sets a goal of 35 percent of city contract dollars go to minorities. City officials declined comment on the ruling and its implications for the program, one of the nation's most recognized and most emulated. `` It is apparent the city had available to it less intrusive means of accomplishing the <ORGANIZATION> MFBE </ORGANIZATION>'s race-conscious purposes but had not fully explored those,'' Justice <PERSON> Willis </PERSON> B. <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> wrote for the seven-member court. It was not immediately clear whether the ruling on behalf of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Subcontractors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> effectively dismantles the program. City Attorney <PERSON> Marva </PERSON> <PERSON> Brooks </PERSON> said an appeal is unlikely, but she said unspecified steps would be taken to save the minority program. Mayor <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON> scheduled a news conference for noon Friday to discuss the ruling. <PERSON> Rodney </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Strong </PERSON>, the city's Contract Compliance director, said he expected that the city would declare a bidding moratorium for a few months on all city contracts, except for emergency situations, while a new program is developed. Among those pleased with the ruling was <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> O. </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Southeastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>, an Atlanta-based public-interest center that joined the lawsuit against the city. `` This means city contracts in the future must be let on a truly competitive basis, with no entrepreneur, black or white, receiving preference,'' <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>'s program has grown steadily since it was created in 1975 by then-Mayor <PERSON> Maynard </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. Some consider it one of the nation's most well-monitored and carefully designed programs of its type The city could appeal to the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. But in January the nation's highest court overturned a similar program in <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va </LOCATION>. Still, <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> officials hoped their program would survive. `` I think there are a number of differences between our case and the <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION> case,'' Mayor <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON> said in January. `` It's the difference between a law based on the spirit of fairness and a law that seems to mandate'' minority set-asides. Last year, the city of <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> awarded $ 29.4 million to minority-owned and operated companies, 36.7 percent of all city contracting business. More than $ 300 million in city business has gone to minority companies since the 35 percent minority participation goal was established in 1975. <LOCATION> Fulton </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> DeKalb </LOCATION> counties have goals of 20 percent minority participation in country contracts. Their programs were not affected by the ruling Thursday.
