<HEAD>Car And Truck Sales Slip 10.5 Percent In February</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Car and truck sales in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> slipped 10.5 percent during February, led downward by a 30.7 percent decline in <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> car sales during the last week of the month, automakers reported Friday. Sales of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and imported cars and light trucks showed declines for late February, for the entire month and for the first two months of this year compared with the corresponding periods of 1988. During the Feb. 21-28 period, car and truck sales reported by the eight domestic vehicle producers were down 14.3 percent this year compared with the same time last year. Vehicles sold at an average daily rate of 46,336 during the period this year, compared with a daily rate of 54,044 vehicles during late February last year. Industry insiders have predicted that 1989 sales will be softer than in 1988, the second-best calendar sales year on record. Part of the reason for the good year last year were strong sales during January and February due to heavy use of incentives. Incentives have been in effect this year, but on a smaller number of cars and light trucks. The sales slides in late February and for the month surprised analyst <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Healy </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. `` They came in lower than I expected,'' he said, adding that some incentives for <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> ended during the last part of the month. `` It's leaving the industry with a lot of inventory.'' <PERSON> Healy </PERSON> estimated that <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> had 85 days' worth, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> 88 and <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> 84. On Friday, <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> announced it was extending for two more weeks a shutdown of its <LOCATION> Doraville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ga. </LOCATION>, assembly plant, which makes Oldsmobile Cutlass Supreme cars. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> blamed the extended shutdown, which affected 4,000 workers, on high inventories. `` We've got too many cars out in the field,'' said <LOCATION> Doraville </LOCATION> plant manager <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>. Among the nation's Big Three automakers, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> alone showed increased sales during late February, the month or during the first two months of the year. But those gains were tiny. The nation's No. 2 automaker said it sold cars at a daily rate of 8,755 during late February this year, up 0.4 percent from the 8,721 daily rate during the same period last year. For the month, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s car sales slipped 2.3 percent and for the year, the company is selling cars at a rate 0.5 percent higher than the same time last year <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s sales of domestic cars skidded 30.7 percent during late February. Analysts and company officials have said the nation's No 3 automaker is suffering a bit from having too little variety in its product lineup. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s monthly sales were off 26.8 percent last month when compared with February a year ago. Car sales during the first two months at <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> are at a pace 18.4 percent below last year's during the same time. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s domestic car sales also fell dramatically compared with last year, dropping 25.4 percent in late February, 17.1 percent for the entire month and 14.6 percent for the first two months of the year.
