<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Nabisco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brands </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> indicated Friday it has been phasing highly saturated tropical oils out of its products since 1987, responding to a multimillionaire health activist's recent attacks on the cookie and cracker maker over the issue In a letter to <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION>, Neb.-based activist <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> Sokolof </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Nabisco </ORGANIZATION> executive stated the company actively has been seeking to reduce the amount of saturated fats in its products. `` Specifically, on the fats of interest to you _ Tropical Oils and Lard _ we are committed to their removal from our products as expeditiously as technology and testing allow; in fact, we believe that we have led our industry in both the timing and number of products that we already have reformulated,'' wrote <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Manfredi </PERSON>, a senior vice president. Saturated fats can increase blood cholesterol levels; high cholesterol is a risk factor for heart attacks. <PERSON> Sokolof </PERSON>, 66, blames high cholesterol for the near-fatal heart attack he suffered 22 years ago. <PERSON> Sokolof </PERSON> said, after a phone conversation Thursday evening with <PERSON> Manfredi </PERSON>, that he had gotten the assurances he wanted. <PERSON> Manfredi </PERSON> followed up with the letter on Friday. `` Yesterday was the first unequivocal announcement,'' <PERSON> Sokolof </PERSON> said in a phone interview. `` I am elated.'' <PERSON> Sokolof </PERSON> says he has spent $ 2 million of his own money on his cholesterol-awareness campaign. In November he placed his first series of full-page ads in five newspapers warning of the dangers of tropical oils such as palm and coconut oil and listing brands that contained them. Since then, 11 other food giants, including <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mills </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGA